<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators seek clues in pier collapse  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN POET
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Investigators removed most of the wooden
planks and plastic chairs from the Delaware River on Friday in a
search for clues to why a nightclub pier collapsed sending dozens
of people into the cool water and killing three women.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Franklin-Suber, Mayor John Street's chief of staff,
said all but two of the 41 people they believe were dropped into
the river had been accounted for. She said authorities don't know
if the two simply haven't checked in with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned and we're not going to give up until they're
accounted for,'' Franklin-Suber said. ''They could be home safe.
They could have left the area.''
</P>
<P>
   City clean-up crews removed most of the debris floating in the
river and stabilized the wrecked pier late Friday, paving the way
for authorities to begin a full-scale investigation Saturday
morning, Franklin-Suber said. Engineers will first examine of the
site by boat launched from the New Jersey shore, then divers will
get a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   All the 20 or so other piers that line the waterfront were ruled
structurally sound by city inspectors late Friday, Franklin-Suber
said. The mayor ordered inspections of all the piers, many of which
are believed to be 100 years old. The former industrial area along
the river is now dotted with restaurants and nightclubs catering to
a college-aged crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern at this point is really to make sure that when
people come out here tonight to visit some of these other piers
that people are safe,'' Fire Commissioner Harold Hairston said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, people at the open-air nightclub Heat said
they had almost no time to react when the pier began falling away
under their feet, plunging dozens of people into the murky water.
One victim said the frantic scene was similar to one in the movie
''Titanic,'' where people ran up an inclined surface as it sank
into the water.
</P>
<P>
   After they hit the cool water, those dropped into the river
desperately tried to reach the surface through a mess of wooden
planks and plastic furniture. An overhead tent fell into the water,
blanketing them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a loud crash, and then all hell broke loose. I went
straight down ... then I was just trying to fight my way up,'' said
bartender Joseph Capaci, 28, of Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   One of the club's employees, Lawrence Price, said he saw a
four-inch crack on the pier that he was told Thursday to cover with
sheet metal. He said he had seen it a week earlier, but it had
grown larger.
</P>
<P>
   Killed were DeAnn White, 25, of Philadelphia; Jean Ferraro, 27,
of Cherry Hill, N.J.; and Monica Rodriguez, 21, also of Cherry
Hill. They were reportedly at the club celebrating White's
birthday, which would have been Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Grief counselors were brought in Friday to the Thomas H. Kean
New Jersey State Aquarium in Camden, N.J., where the three worked.
White, 25, was the aquarium's public relations director, Ferraro
was the marketing director and Rodriguez was a part-time special
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   All but six of the 37 injured have been treated and released.
The others remain in area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the company that owns Heat and the Moshulu said
he was working near the pier Thursday night and stayed on the scene
until early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am distraught and saddened by the tragic accident at Pier
34,'' Eli Karetny, president of HMS Ventures Inc., said in a
statement released Friday. ''I have been involved in restaurant
operations from the pier for many years. The safety of our patrons
has always been of utmost importance. My heart goes out to all our
patrons and employees who were involved and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Karetny said he was cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The city Department of Licenses and Inspections is seeking help
from a forensic engineering firm that specializes in pier design.
The Army Corps of Engineers, responsible for the Delaware River
shipping channel, is helping with clean-up and as a technical
consultant, spokesman Ed Voigt said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the expertise to handle this. It's just too big
for us,'' Licenses and Inspections Commissioner Ed McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   City homicide detectives also were investigating, which police
said is routine after a fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   The river was closed to all ship traffic most of Friday. It
reopened around 11 p.m., though boats had to be escorted by the
Coast Guard overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Harris, a Drexel University engineering professor, said
many of the piers were originally built to support warehouses and
should be able to withstand the weight of a night club.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some are in very bad shape and some are in very good shape,
relatively. It depends on the owner and what transpired,'' Harris
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nightclub opened this month next to the historic Moshulu
ship-turned-restaurant. The restaurant is built into the
394-foot-long tall ship, a turn-of-the-century German cargo ship
that has been converted into an upscale restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking at a Democratic fund-raiser at
Philadelphia City Hall, expressed his sympathy to the city for the
pier accident and said he was being briefed by the Coast Guard and
local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it's a painful thing for the city and I'd like to say
how sorry I am,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
