<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates: Mentally ill inmates fueling prison increases  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- To Dr. Bert Pepper, the burgeoning
population of federal, state and local prisons should prompt those
not behind bars to demand answers.
</P>
<P>
   There are now more than 2 million people incarcerated in the
United States, or about 10 times as many as in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Has there really been a 10-fold increase in criminal behavior in
this country in the past two generations?
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, a psychiatrist, said it is clear there has not been. Nor
does he believe that the jump in the size of the state's prison
system over that same period -- from 19,000 to 72,000 -- can be
explained by the presence of three times as many criminals in New
York society.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pepper is among the advocates for the mentally ill who
believe the influx of the imprisoned is in part a function of a
burgeoning number of people who are not getting proper care for
mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper believes it is hardly a coincidence that while the prison
population has soared, the number of beds available in mental
institutions in New York state has nose-dived, from 93,000 in the
mid-1950s to about 6,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Where have those once institutionalized mentally ill people -- or
at least their modern-day counterparts -- gone? Pepper, once a
deputy mental health commissioner in New York, estimates that
23,000 are in state prisons and 13,000 are in local jails.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since everybody has to be some place ... society has built
them jail cells,'' Pepper said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 24,000 are homeless and 4,000 are living in shelters,
Pepper estimated.
</P>
<P>
   As the mental institution ''balloon'' has been deflated in an
effort to warehouse fewer ill people in hospitals and get them
functioning in society, the prison and jail balloon has been pumped
up ever higher, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   This notion has a tongue-twister of a name among mental health
advocates -- ''transinstitutionalization.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A specific portion (of the mentally ill) has been shifted from
the hospitals and the institutions ... usually by way of the
streets, to prisons and jails,'' said Joseph Glazer, head of the
Mental Health Association of New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Glazer's group and others argue that this process amounts to the
criminalization of mental illness in modern-day American society.
</P>
<P>
   They do not contend that the mentally ill are not committing
crimes which land them in state prison or local jails. But they say
criminal behavior is often a byproduct of the greater failure of
mental health treatment systems to identify people's problems and
make sure they are dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Pepper believes, ''The majority of drug offenders
are mentally ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, who also once headed Maryland's state mental health
system, said when he speaks to jail wardens or prison
superintendents, he tells them, ''Congratulations,'' you have just
become head of a ''mental hospital full of drug addicts -- That's
our prisons today.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Abate, a former state senator who once headed New York
City's jail system, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jail has become the primary care setting for the mentally ill,
especially the homeless,'' she said. ''Jails have become
repositories of the mentally ill in our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, jails and prisons are poor places for mentally ill
people to get better, the advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   In the entire New York City corrections system, with some
126,000 new admissions each year, there are only 368 beds where
mentally ill inmates get 24-hour care and supervision.
</P>
<P>
   In the state prison system, officials say there are about 850
beds set aside in the system for inmates needing more acute,
intensive mental treatment. State officials say about 7,500 inmates
in all receive in- or outpatient mental health treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum in Albany this week sponsored by Glazer's group,
former chief state judge Sol Wachtler said the criminal justice and
the mental health systems have failed the mentally ill at all
levels.
</P>
<P>
   He included the judiciary in that category. Forced to resign in
disgrace after an arrest he blames on an untreated manic depressive
condition, Wachtler said the judge at his own trial was like judges
most everywhere -- she had little knowledge about the effects of
mental problems on the defendants coming before her.
</P>
<P>
   While not insane by the stringent standards of the law,
thousands upon thousands of inmates are in jails and prisons
because of behavior created by mental problems, Wachtler said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judges are not able to draw distinctions,'' Wachtler said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
