<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bragman says his support slips, but vows to continue  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Partisans of Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
are declaring him the winner of a short, sharp challenge to his
leadership position mounted by former Majority Leader Michael
Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is over now,'' Assemblyman Steven Sanders of Manhattan said
Friday. Another Manhattan assemblyman, Richard Gottfried, said,
''It certainly seems to be a mopping-up operation at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   A third Silver supporter, Ronald Canestrari of Albany County,
agreed that, ''Certainly, it is safe to say the speaker will remain
the speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, however, said he would go forward with a resolution
Monday which seeks to suspend the rules of the Assembly so members
can elect a new speaker.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Bragman promised, Silver will discover that a
''significant'' number of Democrats in the Assembly are unhappy
with him and that changes must be made in how the chamber is run.
</P>
<P>
   But Bragman conceded that the support of at least 50 Assembly
Democrats which he thought he had on Wednesday -- enough to be
elected speaker among the 98 Assembly Democrats -- was eroding in
the face of what he called ''atrocious'' arm-twisting by Silver and
those close to the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''Am I still in a position to win? I don't know,'' he told The
Associated Press Friday. ''But you know what? There's going to be
change here. Shelly Silver must go as the speaker of the New York
state Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he was ''not even looking at me being speaker''
anymore, just in ''leading this conference in a new direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about reform,'' he said. ''I don't care what the
penalties are to me, I don't care what the retribution is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, from the Onondaga County suburb of Cicero, said there
might still be three dozen Democrats on Monday willing to oppose
Silver, but Silver's partisan scoffed at that estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is just ridiculous,'' Sanders said. ''He has one of those
two digits, but not the two put together. By the end of the day
today any support that he has had will have evaporated into single
digits.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those Bragman supporters, Martin Luster of Tompkins
County, said Friday that legislators were ''growing weary'' with
the incessant telephone conversations with each side and among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think no matter what happens, Speaker Silver now knows there
are a substantial number of his colleagues in the conference who
are not in agreement with him,'' Luster said.
</P>
<P>
   Luster added, ''Maybe he (Silver) will wind up winning the
battle, but the message is loud and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   A crucial point in the power struggle came on Thursday night
when Assemblyman Robert Ramirez, who is also Bronx County
Democratic leader, showed up arm-in-arm with Silver at a
fund-raiser for Assembly Democrats in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am absolutely, unequivocally, 100 percent behind Speaker
Sheldon Silver,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman had been trying to woo Ramirez to his side.
</P>
<P>
   Silver forces on Friday said Queens Democratic leader Tom
Manton, a Bragman supporter, had made peace overtures to the
speaker. But both Manton and Bragman staunchly denied on Friday
that Manton was seeking any such accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman blamed hardball tactics by Silver for costing him
support. That included threats by the speaker to strip committee
chairmanships from Bragman backers, to run Democratic primary
opponents against them and to redraw their district lines next year
in ways that they could not hope to win re-election starting in
2002, according to Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch denied another Bragman claim
that the speaker had waded into a murky ethical waters by having
lobbyists trying to whip up support for Silver among lawmakers.
Bragman said those same lobbyists will be back trying to curry
favor in the Assembly for legislation their clients want once the
leadership battle is over.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said the ''badgering'' of legislators by lobbyists is
''beyond the law'' and is ''going to have repercussions beyond
these two or three days.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The former majority leader is not in a position at this time
to make outrageous statements such as those,'' Lynch countered.
''It's unfortunate that he continues to try to divide this
conference with such outrageous, inaccurate statements. He should
know better, but then again he should have known better on
Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, an assemblyman since 1980 and majority leader since
1994, said that no matter how the struggle with Silver plays out,
he will not resign from the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will complete this term,'' he said. ''I don't care if I'm
sitting at a desk in the basement. I don't care if I have no
resources available. I will not be threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to Silver, Bragman had the most resources available to an
individual legislator as majority leader. He got a $34,500 a year
stipend as majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Silver is from Manhattan. No Democrat from outside New York City
has been speaker of the state Assembly since 1911.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
