<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snakebite victim knew instantly his life was at risk  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Anthony Cavallaro knew the instant he felt
the needle-sharp fangs of his pet Gaboon viper pierce his hand his
life was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo man grabbed a razor blade and sliced at his flesh
then thrust his hand to his mouth to suck the venom. A friend
called 911 as Cavallaro, in intense pain as the venom spread, began
to vomit.
</P>
<P>
   ''His arm swelled up four times its normal size and it was
turning black,'' Cavallaro's brother, Kevin, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Cavallaro, 40, had been changing the snake's water
Wednesday evening when it struck. Though hospitalized in intensive
care, Cavallaro was improving and able to talk Friday, family
members said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said 'I'm a trooper. I'm pulling through this,''' said his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot Gaboon viper is part of a collection of exotic pets
that also includes a cobra, a rattlesnake, a copperhead, two boa
constrictors and an 8-foot alligator named Albert which Cavallaro
has raised in his home.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaboon viper, whose gray and brown skin resembles an
Oriental carpet, is one of the deadliest venomous reptiles. Native
to South and West Africa, it has the longest fangs of any snake, up
to two inches. Gaboons are capable of biting to the bone and
injecting large quantities of highly toxic venom which attacks
blood and muscle tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is immediate pain and swelling follows in just
minutes,'' said Clyde Peeling, owner of Clyde Peeling's Reptiland
in Allenwood, Pa. Depending on the size of the snake and the amount
of venom injected, ''It could conceivably kill you in less than an
hour but a more likely scenario is 18 hours or two days.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cavallaro fading, emergency workers worked against time to
find serum known as ''antivenin'' to counter the venom's effects.
</P>
<P>
   A call went to the Buffalo Zoo, but with no Gaboon vipers in its
reptile house, there was no antivenin on hand. Zoo officials
advised emergency workers to call Western New York Poison Control,
who in turn called counterparts in Arizona, keepers of a master
list of zoos and the antivenins they stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Bronx Zoo was identified as the closest source,'' said
Rick Paine, the Buffalo Zoo's interim president. The serum was
flown in and administered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zoos have networked for years to make sure there is a master
list so in case of an emergency there is a very efficient mechanism
to locate the antivenin,'' Paine said.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallaro has permits for all of his animals and shows the
snakes, poisonous except for the boa constrictors, his brother
said. While the snakes are housed in large windowed cases, the
alligator wanders the house, often sliding into the bathtub for a
dip.
</P>
<P>
   ''He treats these things like they're humans,'' Kevin Cavallaro
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaboon viper remained in its aquarium Friday, barely moving,
as is typical of the species.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can get lulled into a false sense of security working
around them because they are so lethargic,'' Peeling said. ''Unless
you've seen them kill a rat or something and you realize they are
lightning quick with their bite you might be tempted to believe
they're almost tame and that's certainly not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   A handler at the Long Island Reptile Expo &AMP; Museum was
hospitalized after being bit by a Gaboon viper in December 1997. In
1983, a 16-year-old nearly died after being attacked by two Gaboon
snakes that he allegedly tried to steal from the National Zoo in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 0027 </TRAILER>
