<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poison Kills Fish in Washington  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A poison spill has killed tens of thousands of
fish over the past two days in Rock Creek, one of the main natural
attractions in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified poison entered the water in Maryland's
Montgomery County and affected fish from just south of the Walter
Reed Army Medical Center Annex to the Potomac River, The Washington
Post reported in Saturday editions. Three dozen species of fish,
including shiners and catfish, were affected.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service has placed the creek off-limits for
wading or fishing, although officials expect the poison to
dissipate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Luckett, a fish kill investigator with the Maryland
Department of the Environment, tlold the Post that the creek will
still show effects of the kill a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   The unknown poison apparently entered the creek Wednesday or
Thursday at a point near an industrial park, the newspaper said.
County, state and federal agency officials said they were trying to
determine the nature of the poison and how it entered the creek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
