<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers 11, Giants 10, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Ron Belliard's 10th-inning sacrifice fly scored
pinch-runner James Mouton and the Milwaukee Brewers got a wild
11-10 victory Friday night over the San Francisco Giants, who lost
their seventh straight.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Blanco drew a walk from Robb Nen (0-1) to open the 10th.
Mouton ran for Blanco and stole second, and pinch-hitter Mark
Sweeney sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   Belliard hit a fly to Marvin Benard mid-right field, and a
sliding Mouton beat catcher Bobby Estalella's tag by inches at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee erased a five-run deficit in the seventh inning and
blew a three-run lead in the eighth. The game was just the latest
chapter in an extraordinarily unpleasant homestand for the Brewers,
who won a 16-inning game against Houston on Tuesday before getting
rained out on Wednesday and Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers closer Bob Wickman (1-1) pitched two scoreless innings
for the victory. The first nine innings of Friday's game took more
than four hours to play, and the final game time was 4:21.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers, whose .241 team batting average entering was the
majors' worst, scored eight runs in the seventh while pounding
Livan Hernandez and relievers Aaron Fultz and Ben Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds returned to San Francisco's lineup and hit his 16th
home run. When he left in the sixth, the Giants were cruising with
a 7-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, eight straight batters reached base for
Milwaukee. Charlie Hayes hit a three-run double off Fultz to cut
San Francisco's lead to 7-6 and, after Weber entered the game, Lyle
Mouton hit a game-tying triple.
</P>
<P>
   Following a walk to Marquis Grissom, Jose Hernandez tripled in
two runs and Henry Blanco doubled in Hernandez. Alan Embree
relieved Weber and got two fly balls to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The eight runs and two triples equaled the Brewers' NL team
records for one inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the offensive fireworks were only beginning. The Giants
touched setup man David Weathers for a run-scoring double by
Estalella and a game-tying two-run single by Armando Rios, who
finished with four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 10 in the ninth, Wickman allowed San
Francisco to load the bases with one out. But third baseman Jose
Hernandez's alert throw got a forceout at the plate, and Wickman
struck out Felipe Crespo.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds, who had three RBIs, missed the Giants' previous three
games after a painful back injury he originally thought might put
him out for the season. He showed no ill effects against the
Brewers, hitting a two-run homer to deep center and adding a
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, swept in three-game series at Colorado and
Atlanta, still hasn't won on its nine-game road trip. Jeff Kent had
three hits for the injury-plagued Giants, who also lost J.T. Snow
in the eighth with tightness in his right groin.
</P>
<P>
   The driving rainstorms that postponed Milwaukee's games against
Houston on Wednesday and Thursday were gone, but the gametime
temperature at County Stadium was 44 degrees. Most of the crowd of
12,842 was bundled up in winter coats and gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Rios had a two-run double in the seventh that appeared to break
open the game for San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Jeromy Burnitz became the latest Brewers player to lose
control of his bat in the cold weather. In the sixth inning,
Burnitz's bat flew into the stands behind the Brewers' dugout. No
one was injured. Nearly three weeks ago, Geoff Jenkins broke a bone
in his finger when it collided with the nob of his bat as he lost
control. Jenkins' bat flew into the stands behind home plate and
broke the arm of a female spectator. ... Mueller singled in the
first inning to extend his hitting streak to 15 games. He stayed in
the Giants' lineup even though Russ Davis returned to the team
after missing two games while attending to personal matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
