<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Comeback Forces Game 7  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- By now, the Miami Heat must be talking to
themselves, wondering what it takes to put the New York Knicks
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat will try once more on Sunday in Game 7 of this seesaw
series after the Knicks overcame an 18-point deficit for a 72-70
victory Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the last two years, the Heat have dropped a playoff
elimination game at home to the Knicks. Now they had their chance
to turn the tables. Instead, the tables got turned on them.
</P>
<P>
   Miami owned this game almost all night. Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy lamented over how sometimes his team played like it was old.
And that was before the Heat built an 18-point first-half lead
against a Knicks team that played lackadaisical, listless
basketball for the first 24 minutes, looking, well, very old.
</P>
<P>
   New York seemed done, drowning in a sea of technical fouls and
deliberate fouls, lane violations and turnovers in the lane.
Everything that could go wrong did go wrong and Miami led by 15 at
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, all at once, the lead began to disappear. Suddenly, the
shots that missed badly for the Knicks in the first half, began
falling. The double-digit deficit dwindled from 15 to 10 to five at
the start of the fourth quarter, to two inside of four minutes.
Finally, it was gone completely, the game tied at 70.
</P>
<P>
   Then Allan Houston nailed two foul shots for the winning points
and when Anthony Carter missed a 3-point attempt at the end, the
Heat had to begin thinking about Game 7 and the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were very disappointed,'' coach Pat Riley said of the
Heat. ''They went into the locker room like it was their last
chance. It wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With these two teams, it never seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he had no problem with the foul call on Dan Majerle
that sent Houston to the line.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt they would go to Allan,'' Riley said. ''It was a step
out pick and roll. I'm not making excuses. It was a tough call at
that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley had warned his team at halftime that even with the
15-point lead, they weren't really safe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told them coming out that a lot would be determined in the
first four or five minutes of the second half,'' he said. ''We knew
they had a rush in them.''
</P>
<P>
   New York hit its first five shots to get right back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though they made a great push, we led throughout the
second half. We were up six with three minutes to play,'' Riley
said. ''They made a great run but we kept the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Right up until the end. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   So now these two rivals will tip it off one more time for the
right to play the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll deal with it,'' Riley said. ''We will get right down to
what it's all about. It's two teams with the best game on Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 0044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
