<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Taiwan President Takes Office
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's new president urged both sides of China to
discuss longstanding disputes and seek peace during his inaugural speech
Saturday. Speaking outside the red brick presidential palace, President Chen
Shui-bian said, ''The Cold War has ended. Now is the time to drop confrontations
and hostilities.'' Chen's 50-minute speech had been billed as one of his best
opportunities to relieve building pressure to forge a diplomatic breakthrough
with the island's giant communist neighbor, which has repeatedly threatened to
attack.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rudy Giuliani Out of Senate Race
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Saying he agonized over the decision for days, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani dropped out of the Senate race Friday, abruptly halting an emerging
campaign against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Battling prostate cancer and
with his marriage in turmoil, Giuliani said it wasn't the right time for him to
run for office. Giuliani's departure from the race propels Rep. Rick Lazio, a
relatively unknown Long Island congressman, to the top of a list of Republicans
hoping to replace him in the battle for the Senate seat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philly Pier Debris Probed for Clues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Investigators looked for clues today as they removed
wooden planks and plastic chairs from the Delaware river after a nightclub pier
collapsed yesterday, sending dozens of people into the water and killing three
people. Mayor John Street ordered an inspection of all piers on the river, many
of which support nightclubs and are believed to be 100 years old. The former
industrial area along the river is dotted with restaurants and other nightspots
catering to a college-age crowd. City clean-up crews removed most of the debris
floating in the river and stabilized the wrecked pier late today, so authorities
can begin a full-scale investigation Saturday morning, said Stephanie
Franklin-Suber, the mayor's chief of staff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blair's Wife Gives Birth
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The wife of British Prime Minister Tony Blair gave birth to a
baby boy early Saturday morning -- the couple's fourth child, officials said.
Cherie Blair, 45, and the baby were in good health, officials at Blair's Downing
Street office said. Mrs. Blair had been due to give birth on May 24, but was
admitted to Chelsea and Westminster hospital in west London at midday Friday.
The boy, whose name was not immediately disclosed, becomes the first child born
to a serving British prime minister in 152 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nicaraguan Gunmen Kill Family of 11
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Gunmen firing assault rifles killed 11 adult
members of a single family in Nicaragua and then burned their home, police said
Friday. The attack on Thursday near the town of Siuna, about 200 miles northeast
of Managua, came a day after three soldiers were killed in an ambush in the same
general area, the police said. The lone survivor of the attack, Guadalupe
Montenegro, was once a member of a group of former Sandinista soldiers suspected
of numerous attacks in the area, national police said. The dead, some of whom
were badly burned, included seven women and four men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NRA May Open Times Square Store
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- The sports-themed restaurants in Times Square might be
getting a new neighbor -- the National Rifle Association. NRASports Blast will
offer virtual-reality trap and skeet shooting, outdoor clothing and hunting
accessories. It will also feature a restaurant -- The N.R.A. Grille-- which will
serve wild game. But it won't sell guns. If NRASports Blast opens -- officials
said no lease has been signed and he did not know when the store would open --
it will pit itself against a slew of theme restaurants and stores in the Time
Square area. Besides ESPNZone, there's also Disney store, the All-Star Cafe and
the WWF store and restaurant.
</P>
