<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pastor's Return May Not Be Long  </HEADLINE>
By MARTHA IRVINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A sign outside Broadway United Methodist Church
carries the message of this Sunday's sermon: ''Always Forgive Your
Enemies. Nothing Annoys Them More.''
</P>
<P>
   One week after United Methodists solidified their ban on
same-sex weddings, the quote attributed to gay Irish playwright
Oscar Wilde also could apply to both sides in a divided church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gregory Dell, a pastor suspended for marrying a gay
couple at the church in 1998, has a feeling the rift is unlikely to
go away. For the first time since his church trial more than a year
ago, he says a split from the United Methodist Church may be
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ''The possibility of schism -- that is, a separate denomination --
is one that we have wanted to avoid if there's any way we could
avoid it,'' the 54-year-old pastor said in an interview with The
Associated Press. ''But that's certainly something that will be
under consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell is set to preach again at Broadway, where about a third of
the members are gay, on July 2. But he wonders how long he'll be
there since he still believes it is his pastoral duty to marry
church members -- gay or straight.
</P>
<P>
   But he says it's not as a protest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't be concerned about sending a message to the United
Methodist Church,'' Dell said. ''What I am concerned about is the
people.
</P>
<P>
   ''For folks to believe that they no longer have an option in a
mainstream Protestant church ... that would be tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell was among 29 people arrested -- many of them for the second
time -- during the United Methodist general conference last week in
Cleveland. Bishop C. Joseph Sprague of Chicago and Bishop Susan
Morrison of Schenectady, N.Y., also were among those arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague and Dell both argued that the church should accept gay
marriage, just as it has decided to allow women to be ordained as
pastors and for divorced people to marry in the church.
</P>
<P>
   But about 60 percent of those voting at the conference -- pastors
and lay leaders from all over the country -- made it clear that the
issue was not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I applaud it. I think the church has upheld its position that
has been a part of church teaching for at least 2,000 years,'' said
the Rev. Stephen C. Williams, a pastor in suburban Lombard who
served as prosecutor in Dell's church trial last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The church cannot duck moral and spiritual issues. I think the
church has the fundamental right to define itself.''
</P>
<P>
   While he believes there will be a need to get over bad feelings
from the conference, the Rev. Scott Field, a Naperville pastor who
is a leader in a conservative Methodist movement called Good News,
said ''the church is getting ready to move on to other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrests in Cleveland marked the first time anyone was
physically removed from a United Methodist general conference, a
meeting that is held every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said he was stunned at an atmosphere of
''mean-spiritedness'' at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the course of the disagreement ... there was always a
willingness for people to hold together, even with those with whom
they strongly disagreed,'' Dell said. ''And that disappeared at
this general conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he still believes Dell is misguided on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have great respect for Greg Dell,'' Williams said. ''But I
think on this issue he is tragically and terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his opposition, Sprague is calling for his flock of
Northern Illinois pastors to obey the church's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell remains steadfast.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels to me clear that the United Methodist Church is not
where God is on this issue -- and it's not even where society is,''
Dell said. ''God's not going to leave this alone. I still believe
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Northern Illinois Conference of the United Methodist Church:
http://www.gbgm-umc.org/nillconf
</P>
<P>
   Broadway United Methodist Church: http://www.brdwyumc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 0109 </TRAILER>
