<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cliton Scraps TV Pitch For China  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Advised by congressional Democrats that the
effort could be counterproductive, President Clinton abandoned
plans to make a nationally televised speech to pitch legislation
establishing permanent normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   During a political fund-raising trip to Philadelphia and Chicago
on Friday, Clinton abruptly canceled a five-minute, televised Oval
Office address on behalf of the trade bill that he had scheduled
for Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   His decision followed talks with House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., and other congressional Democrats while on the
flight to Chicago, White House spokeswoman Jennifer Palmieri said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been talking with them for the past couple of days about
what's the most productive way to get votes on this,'' Palmieri
said. ''They've advised us that they don't think that the Oval
Office address is the most productive way to get votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would open China's markets to more U.S. goods, and end
20 years of annual reviews of China's trade status. The bill is
supported by the business community and opposed by labor,
environmental and some veterans' groups. Both sides said the vote
remains close and predicted a weekend of hard lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats had asked Gephardt, an opponent of the
legislation, to deliver a televised response to Clinton's address.
A senior White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said some other lawmakers who had urged Clinton to make the speech
changed their minds Friday, feeling the address would raise the
stakes for the legislation and ''make it more divisive and
high-profile than it needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC and CBS had said they would not carry Clinton's speech. ABC
said the network had already covered both sides of the issue on its
news programs, and CBS said the address amounted to lobbying. NBC,
CNN and Fox had said they would carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., and other supporters of
the trade deal claimed new momentum, citing both a new
China-European Union trade agreement and a side plan backed by the
bipartisan congressional leadership for a watchdog commission to
monitor human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be able to have the votes necessary for a strong
victory,'' said Dreier, chairman of the House Rules Committee. He
said his panel, which sets ground rules for considering bills, will
meet Tuesday, followed by House floor debate on the measure
Wednesday and a vote either late that day or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Five formerly undecided House members -- Democrats John LaFalce
of New York, Thomas Sawyer of Ohio and Diana DeGette of Colorado;
and Republican Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas -- announced their support
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Closing the door on China will not improve human rights in
China. It would be a step back,'' DeGette said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents claimed three new converts to the ''no'' column: Reps.
Robert Andrews, D-N.J.; Rod R. Blagojevich, D-Ill.; and Karen
McCarthy, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
