<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Pirates Plunder Ships  </HEADLINE>
By SLOBODAN LEKIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLOP ISLAND, Indonesia (AP) -- A Colt .45 strapped to his hip,
Sgt. Marwando gazes out at the shimmering sea from a clump of palm
trees, standing guard on the front line of the international war
against piracy.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles to the north, the Singapore skyline adorns the
horizon. Between the affluent city-state and this tiny Indonesian
island inhabited only by a handful of navy frogmen, lies the
world's most congested -- and potentially dangerous -- shipping lane.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow straits of Malacca and Singapore are the most
pirate-infested waterways of the world. Despite the vigilance of
Marwando and his fellow lookouts, the buccaneers have exacted an
increasingly heavy toll on international shipping.
</P>
<P>
   When Philippine rebels on boats recently took 21 hostages from a
resort island in Malaysia, the world's attention was again focused
on this centuries-old problem.
</P>
<P>
   Experts warn that major collisions and ecological disasters
could occur, because the pirates have taken to shackling crews on
their oil tankers and setting the vessels adrift.
</P>
<P>
   In the most extreme cases, crime syndicates employ hardened
criminals who sometimes execute entire crews. The vessels are then
renamed, and their cargos sold at distant foreign anchorages where
corrupt officials can be bribed to look the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to stem the brazen attacks on its side of the narrows,
Indonesia's ill-equipped navy has appealed for foreign donations of
high-tech equipment such as naval radars and computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need night-vision equipment with video cameras to film the
bandits, more speedboats for our frogmen, global positioning
systems, that sort of thing,'' said Col. Boedi Setyadi, commander
of the Batam naval base that controls the Indonesian side of the
straits.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to modernize the service have been crippled by the
United States, Indonesia's traditional source of weaponry, which
imposed a ban last year on military exports following the
destruction of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the London-based International Maritime Bureau's
latest survey, 19 pirate attacks were recorded in Indonesia in the
first three months of this year, compared to 18 cases during the
same period in 1999 and 10 in 1998. That means the waterway
accounts for one-third of all maritime attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, more than 50,000 ships ply the straits, which link
Europe and Asia. An armada of tankers, container ships, liquefied
natural gas carriers and other merchant vessels tail one another in
short intervals as they traverse the five-mile-wide stretch of
water opposite Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The pirates lurk in the countless inlets and mangrove swamps
that dot the coastline of Sumatra or among the hundreds of islets
and reefs near Singapore. Their speedboats quickly slither in and
out of the sea lanes under cover of darkness to plunder and then
run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling up alongside ships, modern swashbucklers use grappling
hooks to hoist themselves onto the vulnerable, heavily laden
vessels. They usually surprise and overwhelm the crews, who are
warned against trying to repel the invaders by force.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping insurers and governments have called for coordinated
action to halt the terror and make the crowded waterway safe for
seafarers. As a result, officials from 16 Asian countries agreed
last month during a Tokyo conference to develop strategies for
fighting piracy in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only government action can eradicate attacks in this area,''
said Neil Choong, a spokesman for the International Maritime
Bureau's regional office in Malaysia. ''As long as there is a
significant naval presence, the number of incidents will be
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   The robberies also frequently go unreported by the victims,
because police investigations entail lengthy delays for ships whose
operating costs can reach $10,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Indonesia's navy chief of staff, Adm. Achmad
Sutjipto, said his service would need to more than double its 114
vessels, many dating back to the 1940s, and 53 aircraft to deploy
effective patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Sutjipto also wants to create a coast guard that would focus on
piracy and smuggling among Indonesia's 17,508 islands.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, warships and maritime reconnaissance aircraft from
Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia have begun joint patrols of the
seaway.
</P>
<P>
   But without night-vision goggles, video cameras and other
surveillance equipment, it's still impossible to effectively
monitor the situation, said Marwando.
</P>
<P>
   ''At night, bandits could attack a ship 500 yards away and we
would know nothing about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they put out to sea in their inflatable boats --
usually after being alerted by passing fishermen -- the frogmen find
it difficult to arrest pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just throw their weapons overboard and pretend they are
fishing,'' said Marwando. ''We can detain them, but we cannot prove
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 0130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Efforts Fail In Zimbabwe  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Three African presidents met with
President Robert Mugabe and publicly praised him as a defender of
the rule of law -- while behind closed doors they demanded he end
political violence and hold free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the tactic used last month -- similar to one used this week
by Commonwealth Secretary-General Don McKinnon -- has failed to
lessen the violence and the intimidation of the political
opposition. Instead, attacks have increased, and many now believe
it's time for the international community to get tough.
</P>
<P>
   Since the African leaders' April 21 summit, at least 14
opposition supporters have been killed and black squatters
supported by ruling party officials have occupied more white-owned
farms.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing has changed,'' said Lovemore Madsuku, vice chairman of
the National Constitutional Assembly, an alliance of civic groups.
''What you need is a clear message to the public that the
international community does not accept this sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence began in February after Mugabe lost a
constitutional referendum that would have entrenched his powers and
given him the right to seize white-owned farms for redistribution
to landless blacks without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Armed squatters and ruling party militants began occupying white
farms, seen as havens of opposition support, and attacking
opposition supporters. At least 21 people, mainly opposition
activists, have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties and human rights groups accuse Mugabe of
orchestrating a campaign of terror to intimidate his opponents
before parliamentary elections called for June, in which the
Movement for Democratic Change party was expected to pose a stiff
challenge to the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   After the summit, South African President Thabo Mbeki,
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano and Namibian President Sam
Nujoma praised Mugabe as a defender of the rule of law and
expressed faith in his efforts to end the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki confirmed to foreign journalists last week that behind
closed doors he told Mugabe the violence must end, the farm
occupations must cease and free and fair elections must be held.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon also treated Mugabe with kid gloves in his public
statements, in which he accepted Mugabe's renewed pledges to stop
the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He genuinely wants to see a lessening of the violence,''
McKinnon said Tuesday. He told reporters he had privately expressed
his concerns to Mugabe about the killings, reportedly taking a
strong tone.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, an opposition supporter was killed and 18 other
people injured in political clashes in Harare.
</P>
<P>
   Critics call Mugabe's pledges insincere.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are making a very wrong assumption that when Mugabe
says violence must end, violence will end,'' said Morgan
Tsvangirai, leader of the Movement for Democratic Change. ''It has
not been working.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the international community's approach been
ineffective, it has disheartened many Zimbabweans looking for
public support and who now might be afraid to vote, said Munyaradzi
Bidi, national director of the human rights organization ZimRights.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders appeared more concerned with maintaining good
relations with Zimbabwe's government than with supporting democracy
and justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is sad that (foreign leaders) feel they must maintain the
rule of law and justice in their own countries,'' Bidi said, ''but
just across the border they do not condemn the violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 0132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handyman Convicted of Sex Murders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- A handyman who sexually assaulted and
murdered four women has been sentenced to four life terms without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Gaynor, 33, on Friday was convicted of aggravated rape
and murder in the deaths in Springfield between November 1997 and
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Thomas, the mother of victim Jo Ann Thomas, 38, had
tears in her eyes after hearing the guilty verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just relieved that this is all over and he just won't hurt
any families,'' said Thomas, who is caring for her daughter's
children, ages 5 and 12. ''They don't know their mother and they
will always be haunted by that.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution said the killer lured the victims by offering
them cocaine, then sodomized them and choked them to death.
</P>
<P>
   The trial hinged largely on DNA tests that linked Gaynor to
semen and blood found on or near the bodies of four women.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor, who was also an auto body repairman, continued to deny
his guilt after the verdicts, telling WGGB-TV of Springfield he was
innocent just before he was taken away in a van.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 0138 </TRAILER>
