<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fusaichi Pegasus Advances  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Watch, wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   That's trainer Neil Drysdale's advice to those already
proclaiming Fusaichi Pegasus the best racehorse in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's won two major races and run six times,'' Drysdale said of
his Kentucky Derby winner, who took on seven challengers in today's
Preakness Stakes. ''We'll see how the year goes.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to form, Fusaichi Pegasus will come
through as the 3-5 favorite to win the Preakness and set up an
unprecedented fourth consecutive year in which the Triple Crown
will be on the line at the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm in '97, Real Quiet in '98 and Charismatic in '99
each won the Derby and Preakness, but fell short in the Belmont.
The last Triple Crown winner was Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too early to be talking about that,'' Drysdale said.
''I'm just interested in getting him ready for this race and into
the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fusaichi Pegasus remains odds-on by post time (5:27 p.m.
EDT), he would be the first Preakness odds-on choice since
Spectacular Bid in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   While Drysdale appeared relaxed on Friday, he said he's still
antsy about the 1 3-16th-mile Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always apprehensive before races,'' Drysdale told a crowd
of reporters and photographers gathered outside the Stakes Barn,
where all the Preakness horses but his are stabled. ''It's a good
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, purchased for $4 million by Fusao Sekiguchi at
the Keeneland yearling select sale, arrived at Pimlico on Wednesday
and has been stabled in Barn 7, located on the remote backside of
Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Tight security went up around the barn the past three days, and
there have been complaints from the media about limited access to
the area.
</P>
<P>
   While Drysdale has expressed concern about protecting his frisky
3-year-old colt, he was unaware of how strict track officials have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time I've heard about that,'' Drysdale said
when told several reporters and photographers were denied access to
see Fusaichi Pegasus at his barn. ''That's crazy. That's not right.
We're here because this is a nice quiet place.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus was to take on four horses he beat in the
Derby, plus and three newcomers, including Red Bullet, the 9-2
second choice. Fusaichi Pegasus beat the Joe Orseno-trained colt by
4\ lengths in the Wood Memorial on April 15. The other non-Derby
horses are Snuck In and Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always been told, 'Don't duck one horse,''' Orseno said.
''You can't says he's not beatable. These are racehorses, not
machines. I don't want to take anything away from him. I just feel
I want to try him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, Captain Steve, High Yield and Hal's Hope, who
finished third, eighth, 15th and 16th in the Derby, respectively,
planned to try again, too.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, trained by Bob Baffert, was the co-third choice
along with Impeachment at 8-1. Captain Steve moved into contention
at the top of the stretch in the Derby, but was bumped by Wheelaway
and dropped back in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I really want to see is the real Captain Steve show up
and run like I know he can,'' Baffert said of his colt who was
winless in four starts this year, but won four times in eight
starts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas was looking for High Yield to return to
his usual contending form after an uncharacteristic race in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think when Pat found out he wasn't going to be 1-2-3, he
saved him,'' Lukas said, referring to jockey Pat Day. ''He might
not run a winning race (today), but he'll have something to say
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert trained Silver Charm and Real Quiet, and understands
what Drysdale is going through in trying to keep a Derby winner in
top condition.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's doing the right thing,'' Baffert said of Drysdale's
decision to keep Fusaichi Pegasus away from the Stakes Barn. ''His
obligation is to his horse, himself and his owner.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he leads him out there, believe me, that horse is ready to
run.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it rained at Pimlico, and the early forecast for
today called for a chance of rain and temperatures in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   An off track would improve the chances of several horses such as
long shots Hal's Hope and Hugh Hefner. However, Drysdale says
Fusaichi Pegasus has trained well on off tracks and ''has the
pedigree to run well'' on one.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the Wood, the colt raced under track conditions
labeled wet-fast.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http//www.pimlico.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
