<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis Trial Could Last Weeks  </HEADLINE>
By CHAD ROEDEMEIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Fulton County Superior Court Judge Alice D.
Bonner is not pleased with the predicted length of the murder trial
of Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is expected to be finished Monday, and opening
statements should begin Tuesday. But the trial could last for
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard said Friday it will take at least
a week for the state to present its version of the fight that left
two men fatally stabbed after a Super Bowl party in Buckhead on
Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, during jury selection, Bonner told lawyers that the
trial should last no more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys, who will present their case after the
prosecution, have complained about the amount of time the district
attorney expects to take.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is zero need for 130 prosecution witnesses,'' said David
Wolfe, attorney for defendant Reginald Oakley. ''The bottom line
is, but for the notoriety that has been affixed to this case, it
ought to take about a week to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said in court documents that the defendants
chased down Jacinth ''Shorty'' Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24,
and started fighting with them after an argument at the Cobalt
Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for Lewis have said the 25-year-old NFL star
didn't stab anyone and acted as a peacemaker. Oakley and Joseph
Sweeting are also charged with murder in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The court finished qualifying the jury pool Friday, and the
final jury will be selected Monday. That means opening statements
and testimony will begin Tuesday, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers asked potential jurors questions Friday designed to
reveal their background, opinions and hidden biases.
</P>
<P>
   One man, Juror No. 98, was excluded after he told prosecutors,
''It's been apparent that the defendants were involved, and I
haven't seen anything that makes me think they weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   That got the man out of jury duty, but not without a stern
reprimand from the judge: ''I hope you never need a criminal
defense lawyer, or anyone you know, love or care about does.''
Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   The only other preliminary business will be a hearing Monday on
whether a statement Lewis gave to police on the morning after the
killings is admissible in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
