<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani drops out of Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani ended an excruciating
three weeks of speculation about his health and marriage by
shutting the door on his bid for the U.S. Senate, less than two
weeks before the state Republican Party's nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, a relatively unknown Long Island
congressman, said he would likely seek the gritty former
prosecutor's place on the GOP ballot against Hillary Rodham
Clinton, the nation's only first lady to run for elected office.
Lazio was scheduled to announce his candidacy this afternoon in
West Islip.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he would seek a little shelter from the spotlight
while he decides how to treat the prostate cancer he was diagnosed
with last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to think the core of me was in politics, probably. It
isn't,'' Giuliani said. ''When you feel your mortality and your
humanity you realize that the core of you is first of all being
able to take care of your health ... so you can be useful to the
people you really care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who turns 56 on May 28, appeared uncharacteristically
nervous as he made the announcement at a packed City Hall news
conference. He spoke in the softer, less certain voice he has
adopted since announcing his illness on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement Friday was made before about 40 television
cameras and a standing-room-only crowd in a public hearing room in
City Hall. City Council Republicans, his deputy mayors, campaign
staff and volunteers crowded the front pews, and rose to their feet
and applauded for a full minute when the mayor appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he expected to have the strength to carry out his
duties as mayor, but it was uncertain whether his ability to govern
would be hurt by the political fallout from his leaving the Senate
race or the turmoil in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank God that it gives me really another 18 months to be
the mayor of New York City,'' Giuliani told the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he would redouble efforts to reach out to those
New Yorkers left behind despite the city's economic renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to try to reach out to more people to try to help
more people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate future, Giuliani must choose a treatment for
his cancer, a decision he has repeatedly said has been far more
difficult than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to deal with it clearly and completely as a personal
matter,'' he said. ''I'm going to ask you to give me a little space
to be able to make that decision properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he informed a coterie of friends before calling
Gov. George Pataki, state Republican Party chairman Bill Powers and
others, including Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush, the
expected Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she had spoken with the mayor shortly after
his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I called him at the conclusion of his announcement to wish him
well, to tell him that I knew this was a difficult decision and I
certainly hope and pray ... that he will have a full and speedy
recovery,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's departure from the race propels Lazio to the
forefront of Republicans hoping to replace him in the battle for
the Senate seat being vacated by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview Friday evening on CNN, Pataki, who has said
he would not seek the seat, voiced his support for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio has earned the nomination and has earned the right
to be our next senator,'' Pataki said. ''He's got an outstanding
record in Washington. He's been a fine congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what would happen to the $9 million
the Giuliani campaign has left from about $20 million raised by a
well-oiled fund-raising apparatus, much of it with solicitation
letters sent around the country to right-wing voters.
</P>
<P>
   By federal campaign law, he is allowed to give only a maximum of
$2,000 directly to another candidate, though he could donate it to
Republican Party committees that in turn could help finance another
candidate's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's decision caps an extraordinary three weeks, beginning
with his disclosure April 27 of his cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, when newspapers began reporting his late night
dinners in the company of a woman not his wife, the mayor described
the woman, Judith Nathan, 45, as a ''very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, Giuliani stunned observers, and his wife of 16 years
-- television personality and actress Donna Hanover, 50 -- by
announcing he would seek a legal separation from her.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Hanover held her own news conference where
she said the mayor had previously had a relationship with one of
his top City Hall aides, Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Both Giuliani and Lategano-Nicholas, 35, who is now head of the
city's tourism bureau, have denied a romantic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as the mayor made his announcement, Hanover was at
Gracie Mansion with the couple's two children, Andrew, 14, and
Caroline, 10.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor called Donna before the announcement and they talked
briefly and she's concerned for his health and will try to help
with that,'' said Hanover's spokeswoman, Joannie Danielides.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Hanover's office confirmed she had hired an
attorney to handle her impending separation from Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 0224 </TRAILER>
