<DOCNO> APW20000520.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori Stays on Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori's hips clumsily
gyrated to his campaign theme song in front of thousands of
flag-waving supporters in the northern fishing port of Chimbote.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's iron-fisted president was back on the campaign trail
Friday, battling for re-election against upstart Alejandro Toledo,
who has raised allegations of fraud and refused to participate in a
May 28 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With an instructive wave of Fujimori's arm, the music stopped,
and the crowd became silent.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Peru we have recovered peace,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have struggled against terrorist violence and we will not
permit any kind of violence to reappear here,'' Fujimori said.
''Especially not in Chimbote.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, police used tear gas to drive back demonstrators
who threw bottles and rocks at the campaign rally in Chimbote, 225
miles northwest of the capital, Lima. Police formed a human barrier
to keep the protesters from the 61-year-old president when he
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who demanded Thursday that the vote be postponed until
June 18 to correct irregularities from the first-round election on
April 9, shows no signs of slowing down either.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot participate in the May 28 election because it is
going to be an ambush,'' Toledo shouted at a massive street rally
in downtown Lima. ''They want us to participate in a fraudulent
process that is already decided.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, independent monitors were denied access to
tabulation centers during the tallying of votes. Final results
showed that about 1 million more ballots were cast than there were
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo supporters, many of them students, held similar rallies
Friday night in major cities across the nation to try to pressure
Fujimori into reconsidering his demand to postpone the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a new consciousness growing. It's not like before,''
said Roberto Cuba, 23, who came to cheer on Toledo. The accounting
student rejected Fujimori's characterization of Toledo's supporters
as ruffians who seek a resurgence of the political violence that
was tamed during Fujimori's 10-year presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the 1980s there were terrible protests associated with
subversion, with terrorism,'' he said. ''Now the people are
protesting because the young are thinking in another manner.''
</P>
<P>
   A commission of election monitors from the Organization of
American States has also sought a postponement of the second-round
vote. However, the election board, controlled by Fujimori
appointees, rejected the request.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department supported the OAS request for a delay
and regretted Toledo's decision to withdraw, as well as the
election board's ''hasty ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional experts agreed that Peruvian electoral laws do
not provide for a candidate to withdraw after elections have been
called and predicted the National Election Board would allow the
runoff to take place over Toledo's objections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
