<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Uncertain on MLK Papers  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two experts advising Congress on whether to
pay $20 million for Martin Luther King's post-1960 papers have
reached conflicting conclusions, further clouding the issue for
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   An appraiser of historical documents found the material
''absolutely stupendous'' and a bargain. King's Pulitzer
Prize-winning biographer determined the documents and artifacts
were of little research value and hardly worth becoming the Library
of Congress' most expensive purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is trying to sort through the analyses, and the
lawmaker who first proposed the idea of the purchase now doubts
whether it will go through.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't do this purchase, I envision some wealthy white
family going to an auction house, getting the papers, and then
selling them back to this same government 20 years from now for
$100 million,'' said Rep. James Clyburn.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina Democrat, who is black, persuaded President
Clinton to include money for the purchase in his budget proposal
last year.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are most of the post-1960 documents now at Atlanta's
Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social Change. King's
early materials are at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   David Garrow, an Emory University professor and biographer of
the slain civil rights leader, told congressional Republicans the
collection has little research value.
</P>
<P>
   He contends the most important documents, called the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference papers, are part of a separate
collection at the King Center. King founded the SCLC, a civil
rights organization, in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Historians contend the SCLC papers were separated from the other
documents at the King Center -- almost randomly. But King's
relatives have refused to make the SCLC papers part of any sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes perfect sense for the Kings to want to get out of the
historical archives business, but the King Papers are not worth $20
million,'' Garrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the library sent a group to Atlanta to
re-examine the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Included among the papers are items that King's widow, Coretta
Scott King, has kept in her home, such as her husband's books from
college and divinity school. But Garrow, who says he reviewed the
entire collection, contends most of the items have autograph value
at best.
</P>
<P>
   ''The great bulk of the King Papers is incoming fan mail from
the general public and the SCLC papers, which Congress can't
have,'' Garrow said.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp disagreement is Willis VanDevanter, who appraised the
papers for the library. He concluded that the asking price was fair
and called Garrow's assessment ''absolute poppycock.''
</P>
<P>
   VanDevanter said the SCLC documents held little value compared
with the rest of the Atlanta collection.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a number of self-anointed preachers who seem to
think they're the authority on the papers, but this is absolutely
stupendous material,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's, the New York auction house, appraised the papers at
$30 million, and VanDevanter's estimate was just a little below
that. The King family has told Clyburn it would settle for $20
million to keep the papers under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   But some in Congress have questioned the family's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I suppose from that standpoint, the King family would have us
believe we're getting a bargain,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga. ''They
have an interest in jacking up the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cost, other questions have emerged. Among them:
Which documents would be included? Does the library already own any
of them on microfilm? And would the intellectual property rights go
to the library or would researchers have to petition the King
family to use the material?
</P>
<P>
   A family spokesman refused to answer these questions and said no
family member would be available to talk about the proposed sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concern is that Congress is being duped,'' said Louise
Cook, who was the director of the King Library, Archives and Museum
when the papers arrived in the 1980s. ''I don't think Congress
understands that they're not getting everything they should get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
