<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Displeased With Taiwan Chief  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China parried newly inaugurated Taiwan President
Chen Shui-bian's calls for peace talks Saturday by accusing him of
insincerity and warning that unification could not be postponed
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The statement issued by the Taiwan office of the State Council,
China's Cabinet, and the Taiwan department of the ruling Communist
Party's Central Committee was restrained in tone but it reiterated
Beijing's threats that moves toward independence would mean war.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anyone dares to try to split Taiwan from China, he will
bear historical responsibility for causing a resumption of China's
civil war,'' said the statement carried by the official Xinhua News
Agency and read on state-run television.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan split amid civil war 51 years ago, and Beijing
has threatened to attack if the island seeks formal independence or
stalls indefinitely on starting talks on unification.
</P>
<P>
   Following Chen's election in March, Chinese leaders urged him to
prove his good intentions by explicitly recognizing Taiwan is part
of ''one China.'' In his speech, however, Chen made only a passing
reference to that demand, saying he believed leaders on both sides
have the ''wisdom and creativity to jointly deal with the question
of a future 'one China.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government's statement expressed dissatisfaction,
although it acknowledged Chen's promises not to declare
independence or to demand China treat Taiwan as a separate,
sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's inaugural speech ''avoided the crucial issue of accepting
the one-China policy; the attitude is evasive and vague,'' it said.
''Obviously, his 'goodwill reconciliation' lacks sincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government statement also repeated Beijing's
willingness to resume talks with Taipei, but only if the Taiwan
side clearly ''commit themselves to adhering to the one-China
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Acceptance of the one-China principle is the touchstone of
whether or not the Taiwan leader will safeguard national
sovereignty and territorial integrity or will continue to
stubbornly pursue the separatist policy of 'Taiwan independence,'''
it said.
</P>
<P>
   China appeared unlikely to take any sudden, drastic actions. Its
leaders have pledged to wait and see what Chen, Taiwan's first
president from an opposition party, does after his inauguration.
Most suspicious to Beijing is his Democratic Progressive Party's
support for independence, although Chen has backed away from that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Chen's speech China's state-run media briefly ceased
attacking Chen; for the first time in weeks, the morning papers
carried no commentaries on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The sole exception was the military newspaper People's
Liberation Army Daily, which ran a half-page, page-three
advertisement declaring ''China can not be broken'' in English and
Chinese. It included a ceramic dragon patterned plate with a small
piece broken off from the lower right-hand side -- similar to
Taiwan's proximity toward the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Future in Lebanon Unknown  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDON, Lebanon (AP) -- These are heady days for Hezbollah, the
Shiite Muslim guerrilla army that spent nearly two decades locked
in bloody battle to drive Israeli troops out of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, on the eve of what Hezbollah calls a glorious victory,
its future has never been more uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   With the last Israeli troops to be gone from south Lebanon
within weeks, Hezbollah's fighters could find themselves rebels
without a real cause -- and perhaps, ultimately, without a patron.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla group is vowing to fight on. But in reality, its
continued existence as an armed force hinges on whether its backer,
Syria, chooses to pursue peace with Israel or allows the guerrillas
to keep waging a proxy war after Israel's pullout.
</P>
<P>
   In the rocky hills of south Lebanon, Israel's exodus -- to be
completed by a self-imposed deadline of July 7, but probably sooner
-- is accelerating. Military hardware is rolling back across the
border, and Israeli soldiers have been handing over heavily
fortified positions to their allied militia, the South Lebanon
Army.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and military sources estimate that only a few hundred
Israeli troops remain, hunkered down in bunkerlike outposts,
keeping movements to an absolute minimum to limit exposure to
relentless guerrilla artillery attacks. Three Israeli soldiers were
hurt, two seriously, in such strikes last week.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, which lost more than 1,000 soldiers in the 18-year
conflict, says it is pulling out of Lebanon on its own terms, and
for its own reasons. But Hezbollah, unsurprisingly, is full of
colorful boasts of how its fighters inflicted humiliating defeat on
the much-vaunted Israeli military machine.
</P>
<P>
   ''We raise our flags while theirs burn,'' said Sheik Nabil
Kaouk, a gimlet-eyed, turban-clad senior Hezbollah commander.
''Their soldiers hid in bunkers that became their graveyards.
Israel tried to establish a state in south Lebanon, but all their
schemes failed miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say the coming weeks could be bloody ones. Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak says the pullout will proceed as planned
no matter how fiercely the guerrillas attack -- ''We are not leaving
a rose garden,'' the former general says bluntly -- while Hezbollah
has been making fire-breathing pronouncements to the effect that
the last Israeli troops will be lucky to get out alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do they expect a farewell present from us?'' said Kaouk, 37, a
veteran Hezbollah fighter. ''We'll give them gifts -- more bodies of
their dead to bring home.''
</P>
<P>
   Until lately, Hezbollah was close-mouthed about its intentions
once the Israelis were gone. But it recently declared its fighters
will not lay down their weapons as long as Israel's allied militia,
the South Lebanon Army, is active and armed.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking simultaneously to terrorize the SLA and woo potential
defectors, Hezbollah's leader, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, warned
militiamen there would be no mercy after Israel departs. ''By God,
we will enter your homes and slaughter you in your beds!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the guerrillas offered clemency to any
SLA soldier who kills an Israeli soldier, or one of his own
officers.
</P>
<P>
   While Hezbollah's appetite for battle might be undiminished in
the wake of the Israeli withdrawal, the same cannot be said for the
Lebanese public.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas' fight to drive out Israel has been a popular
cause nationwide, even when Hezbollah's cross-border attacks have
brought Israeli reprisals down on all of Lebanon. After Israeli
troops have left, though, that could quickly change.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be an entirely different calculation then,'' said
Farid el-Khazen, a political scientist at the American University
of Beirut. ''If Hezbollah is seen as causing more fighting --
fighting that people see as unnecessary -- public opinion would turn
against them. And they are very, very sensitive to public
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true now, as Hezbollah seeks to wield greater
political influence. Parliamentary elections are due this summer,
and the group -- drawing on electoral backing from among 1.2 million
Shiite Muslims, Lebanon's largest sect -- hopes to build on the
seven seats it now holds in the 128-member body.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the war front, Hezbollah has become a formidable
social force, building a network of schools, clinics and social
services. In the group's stronghold of south Beirut, a gleaming,
marble-floored Hezbollah hospital boasts the latest lab equipment
and offers health care at a deep discount to the neighborhood's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not done to gain political support -- this is our
community,'' said hospital administrator Mohammed Hijazi.
</P>
<P>
   But as Islamic groups throughout the region know, such
on-the-ground services can translate into a loyal following. ''I
ask God to bless them ... We must do all we can to advance their
goals,'' said Nawal Yassin, 33, swathed in a black veil and
cradling her sick 11-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   A similar investment in the future is being made at Hezbollah's
10 schools nationwide. The curriculum emphasizes Koranic studies,
with celebrations of holidays like the Week of the Islamic
Resistance, but students also get a solid grounding in math, hard
sciences and foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people think of Hezbollah fighters as terrorists,'' Ahmed
Kasir, principal at the flagship south Beirut campus. ''But we try
to teach the children that our fight with Israel is a legitimate
one, and that being martyred for an important cause is an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Created with Iranian backing in 1982, Hezbollah has become much
less militant as time has passed. In its shadowy early years, it
was linked, despite its denials, to the 1983 bombing of a Marine
Corps barracks in Beirut that killed 241 U.S. servicemen and to the
kidnappings of dozens of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   These days, even the movement's most ardent partisans
acknowledge that Hezbollah's longstanding goal of an Islamic state
in Lebanon -- a country splintered among 18 recognized sects -- is an
unlikely dream.
</P>
<P>
   Beirut, a cosmopolitan playground before huge swaths of it were
leveled in the 1975-1990 civil war, is now engaged in a frenzy of
rebuilding heavy on luxury hotels, plush office buildings and swank
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hezbollah's young enforcers roamed the capital, trying to
curb un-Islamic behavior like card-playing and bar-hopping. Now the
group's home turf in south Beirut is dotted with American fast-food
chains, and one of its offices is upstairs from the Romance
Lingerie Boutique, featuring a windowful of skimpy lace underwear.
</P>
<P>
   The big decisions about Hezbollah's future, though, are not
likely to be made on the battlefield, at the ballot box, or in its
own suites of offices -- but rather in Iran and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is believed to provide the group with $10 million to $20
million a month, and Syria serves as the principal conduit for its
cash and weaponry. Some diplomats believe that if Hezbollah is seen
as having served its purpose in south Lebanon, the money and arms
will dry up.
</P>
<P>
   After the Israeli pullout, Syria could keep sponsoring Hezbollah
strikes on Israel itself to try to force a peace deal resulting in
a handover of the Golan Heights. But that would carry the threat of
Israeli retaliation against Syrian targets, a risk Damascus might
be unwilling to run.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, which has lost more than 1,250 fighters since 1982,
is eager to keep up the battle, even once it is deprived of an
unambiguous goal -- forcing Israel out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our Islamic beliefs make us strong in our ability to
sacrifice,'' Kaouk said. ''There is no reason for this to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
