<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Hezbollah Guerrillas  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some facts about Hezbollah:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY -- Formed in 1982 with Iranian backing during Israel's
invasion of Lebanon. Secretive in early years, linked to bombing of
U.S. Marine barracks in 1983, bombings of two U.S. Embassy
buildings, kidnappings of more than 50 foreigners. More politically
moderate in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LEADERSHIP -- Factions remain, but clear leadership exercised by
secretary-general Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah, who took over after 1992
assassination of Sheikh Abbas Musawi.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY -- Stages attacks on Israeli soldiers in south Lebanon
and on Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army. Fewer than 500 Hezbollah
fighters believed in field, but thousands of armed supporters
across Lebanon. Armed mainly with mortars, rockets,
rocket-propelled grenades and rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   CONSTITUENCY -- Draws support from Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiite
Muslims, country's biggest sect. Popular in southern Lebanon, Bekaa
Valley in eastern Lebanon, poor southern suburbs of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   CHARITY WORK -- Operates schools, hospitals, dental clinics.
Provides drinking water to Beirut slums, rebuilds roads and houses
destroyed in fighting in south.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   FUNDING -- Iran estimated to provide $10 million-$20 million
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS -- Seeks Islamic government for Lebanon, which has 18
officially recognized religious sects. Can draw tens of thousands
of supporters to rallies. Runs TV and radio stations, weekly
newspaper, Internet site. Seven members in Lebanon's 128-seat
parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
