<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Had 'Home Field' Benefit  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYRE, Lebanon (AP) -- The pages of military textbooks are full of
matchups like this one. A small band of guerrillas, fighting on
home turf, takes on a far more powerful invading army. Which one
wins?
</P>
<P>
   Israel insists it didn't suffer a military defeat in southern
Lebanon. Nonetheless, its troops are leaving -- and the Shiite
Muslim fighters of Hezbollah, who led the fight to drive them out,
are declaring victory.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime diplomatic and military observers of the conflict paint
a portrait of a guerrilla army whose determination, ingenuity and
ruthlessness made up for its small, relatively low-tech arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   During the nearly two decades of Israeli occupation, Hezbollah
rarely fielded more than several hundred guerrillas at any given
time, but had thousands of armed supporters. Its ranks were largely
drawn from Shiite Muslim villages of southern Lebanon, giving its
fighters not only an intimate knowledge of the terrain -- which they
exploited to the fullest -- but also the support of local people.
</P>
<P>
   Israel allied itself with a locally recruited, partially
conscripted militia force, the South Lebanon Army, whose ranks were
highly susceptible to infiltration, security experts say. While
Israel had detailed aerial surveillance on its side, Hezbollah's
intelligence from human sources was often superior.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and SLA increasingly took to fortified bunkers to
defend themselves, but Hezbollah fighters stayed on the move,
staging hit-and-run attacks and slipping away before Israeli air
strikes could be called in.
</P>
<P>
   The core of Hezbollah fighters developed years of battlefield
experience. Israeli soldiers, most of them young, usually served
rotations lasting only a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's battlefield losses -- 1,259 dead since 1982, by its
own count -- did not daunt the guerrillas, whose ideology glorified
martyrdom. With close to the same level of losses -- more than 1,000
dead -- Israeli public support for a pullout mounted along with the
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah was by no means immune to costly errors. In earlier
days, it staged reckless human-wave assaults on Israeli positions.
It also engaged in a long and bloody power struggle with Amal, a
rival Shiite militia.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's arsenal was relatively unsophisticated, consisting
mainly of sniper rifles, mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and
Soviet-designed Katyusha rockets. It used technology sparingly, but
with devastating effect: night-vision equipment to ambush patrols,
remote-detonated roadside bombs that killed some top Israeli
commanders and armor-piercing rockets capable of destroying
Israel's massive Merkava battle tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel learned that its weapons were not enough,'' said Sheik
Nabil Kaouk, a senior Hezbollah commander. ''It was a war of minds.
... For all our problems on the battlefield, we found solutions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
