<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Heart Devices  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Saturday he wants
heart-starting defibrillators placed in federal office buildings
and airplanes to help save the lives of people who suffer sudden
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency devices, which use electric shock to start a heart
in cardiac arrest, are already becoming available at shopping malls
and businesses. Clinton said one recently was used to save a life
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key of survival is the speed of response,'' Clinton said
in his weekly radio address. ''In addition to CPR, most cardiac
arrest victims need an immediate electrical shock to restore the
heart's normal rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When victims receive that shock within a minute, there's a 90
percent chance of resuscitation,'' he said. ''When it takes 10
minutes, the odds fall to less than 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will direct the Department of Health and Human
Services and the General Services Administration to write
guidelines for putting defibrillators in all federal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   To support the effort, three manufacturers will donate the
devices. The American Red Cross and the American Heart Association
have volunteered to train federal employees in using
defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they foresaw the need.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am happy to say that after many years of hard work on
promoting external defibrillators, the House of Representatives
will vote on legislation on Tuesday to help save the lives of
cardiac arrest victims,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman
of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the newest models are about the same size and price
of a laptop computer, use voice commands to lead users through each
step and deliver a shock only if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   About 250,000 Americans suffer from sudden cardiac arrest each
year, according to the heart association. About 5 percent survive.
Cardiopulmonary resuscitation can buy time, but cannot restart a
heart. Defibrillators can jolt a heart into beating again.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced that the Federal Aviation Administration
will soon require airlines to carry defibrillators on all domestic
and international flights. Eight major and six regional airlines
either now carry or have made a commitment to carry defibrillators,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines will have three years to buy the defibrillators and
develop training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of American Airlines applauded Clinton's announcement,
saying 11 passengers have been saved by the devices since they were
installed on the carrier's planes in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he supported a bill that the House
Commerce Committee's health and environment panel approved earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, introduced by Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., aims to
get defibrillators in federal buildings and also grant legal
immunity to people who use them to help someone suffering from
sudden cardiac arrest in public or private buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just last week a visitor here at the White House collapsed and
would have died if not for one of the AEDs (automated external
defibrillators) that our medical unit acquired last year,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
