<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentalists call GE's Hudson River ads misleading  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM F. HAMMOND Jr.
The Daily Gazette
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- General Electric Co.'s new advertising
campaign against dredging PCBs from the Hudson River is
''misleading'' and ought to be withdrawn by the company,
environmental groups said.
</P>
<P>
   The ads began appearing in newspapers and on radio and TV last
week. They highlight the fact that many local governments in the
upper Hudson Valley are on record opposing a dredging project
currently being weighed by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some activists are urging the EPA to order dredging in the
Hudson,'' one of the newspaper ads reads. ''But elected leaders in
over 50 communities have voted against it. The river has made a
remarkable comeback. Let's think hard before we undo all the good
that's been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, who passionately support dredging,
denounced the ads as misleading ''propaganda'' designed to stir up
public opposition. They said many of the town resolutions against
dredging were taken more than three years ago, and don't
necessarily reflect current public opinion in those communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here to tell you that the people in the North Country are
on propaganda overload,'' said David Higby of Environmental
Advocates, who lives in Salem, Washington County. ''I'm part of
that community, and I'm not of that mind. So I'm offended.''
</P>
<P>
   They also say that 60 municipalities farther south in the Hudson
Valley, along with 40 community groups, are on record in support of
a cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is essentially lying with statistics,'' said Andrew Mele
of the Hudson River Sloop Clearwater. ''You just don't show the
part of the picture that refutes what you're claiming.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Behan, a GE spokesman, said it's the environmentalists
who are stretching the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amusing that environmental groups would seek to deny that
there is widespread opposition to dredging in the upper Hudson
River,'' Behan said. ''They know it well.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that many of the local governments adopted their
anti-dredging resolutions years ago, but he said GE checked to make
sure they had not changed their position. Some have recently
reconfirmed their votes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Behan also said he doubted very many local governments have
formally taken the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there were 60 communities that supported dredging in the
Hudson River, they would have produced a list a long time ago,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   GE plants in Hudson Falls and Fort Edward legally dumped waste
water containing PCBs into the Hudson River for several decades,
until the practice was banned in the 1970s. The EPA is now studying
whether sediments contaminated with the chemicals, which are
suspected of causing various health problems, should be dredged at
the company's expense. A decision from the agency is expected late
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 1317 </TRAILER>
