<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Arrests Suspect in Bombing  </HEADLINE>
By ZAIRA MAGOMEDOVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Police arrested a suspect Saturday in
an apartment bombing that killed 64 people in the republic of
Dagestan last year, the first of a series of attacks across Russia
that helped bring about the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   An Interior Ministry official in the Dagestani capital of
Makhachkala said that Isa Zainutdinov, a Dagestani resident, was
suspected of being a ''major perpetrator'' of the bomb attack on an
apartment building in Buinaksk.
</P>
<P>
   According to the spokesman, 62-year-old Zainutdinov admitted he
drove a truckload of explosives to the apartment block, but claimed
that he was unaware of its intended use. The blast shattered an
apartment block that housed military officers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing was the first of four apartment blasts around Russia
last September that left about 300 people dead. Russia blamed the
attacks on rebels from Chechnya, which neighbors Dagestan, but had
yet to report any major breakthroughs in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops entered Chechnya in September after
Chechnya-based Islamic militants seized several villages in
Dagestan and the wave of attacks on apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Chechnya on Saturday, the Russian military command said
federal forces repelled a band of rebels attempting to infiltrate
two towns in Russian-controlled central Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops opened fire on the guerrillas as they
attempted to approach the towns of Shali and Serzhen-Yurt, 11 miles
southeast of the capital Grozny, on Friday, and forced them to
retreat to a stronghold near the village of Mashtak to the south,
the command's press center said.
</P>
<P>
   Two rebels were killed in the clash, the command claimed. There
was no report of Russian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The press center again warned that the rebels may intensify
their guerrilla campaign on the orders of rebel Chechen President
Aslan Maskhadov. ''His earlier circulated order to the rebels was
to step up combat against federal forces at this time,'' the center
said.
</P>
<P>
   The military has been saying for a week that Maskhadov has
ordered rebels to go on the offensive this weekend, but many
militants operate outside Maskhadov's control and a new major
military offensive has yet to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   The command said groups of rebels, led by field commander Shamil
Basayev and the warlord known as Khattab, were operating in eastern
Chechnya, near Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The extremists tend to concentrate near populated areas where,
despite the local population's resistance, they try to replenish
their food supplies and obtain information on the federal troops'
activity,'' the command said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
