<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four debates in eight days leave Corzine unscathed and Florio scrambling </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. (AP) -- For Jim Florio, outspent by a candidate who
has most of the Democratic Party's weight on his side, last week's
debates in the primary race for U.S. Senate were a much-awaited
chance at an even playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days and four debates later, while Florio had shown
himself the more skilled speaker, it was nevertheless he who was
hobbling off that even field.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine did appear rattled occasionally by the pressure of the
debates and the harsh barrages of an opponent whose answers and
attacks were more compactly phrased. But Corzine made no blunder
that would haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He survived,'' said Rider University political analyst David
Rebovich. ''I agree with folks who say he was nervous. He did
stumble a couple of times. But the debates did not disqualify
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebovich said Florio got the chance at the most exposure to date
for his campaign effort and it ended up as something of a missed
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florio would have been wiser, instead of just attacking
Corzine for the Goldman Sachs connection, he should have tried to
turn the debate into more specifics,'' Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with two weeks to go and Corzine refusing an invitation to
debate on network television, the race returns to traditional
street campaigning and Corzine's heavy spending, roughly $17
million to $20 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   More than missing chances to score, Florio by the end of the
debate cycle was blocking punches after a mistake of his own
regarding a flip-flop of views on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly New Jersey Jewish News released a tape recording of
Florio in May 1999 endorsing the investment of a small fraction of
Social Security funds in the stock market, but since then Florio
has caustically attacked Corzine for proposing the exact same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake came out as a result of the debates.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish News editor, David Twersky, said Florio in the first
debate on New Jersey Network implied the reporter who wrote it had
admitted being wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reporter indicated there may have been some
misunderstanding. There are no quotes,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   Twersky said that answer ''kind of got my Irish up and I asked
the reporter for her notes, and she found the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   It had Florio saying: ''I have no difficulty with a relatively
small, segmented portion of the Social Security trust fund monies
being put into equities, and we should put them in, in the same way
that we put those types of resources into teachers' funds and other
public agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio ended his denunciations when the tape was made public. At
Thursday's final debate he said, ''The transcript that came out
clearly indicates I misspoke. I did not think it was a good idea in
the past. I do not think it is a good idea now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign denounced Florio as a liar, and Rebovich
said it undercut Florio's attempt to portray himself as a veteran
who knows what he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really is unbelievable,'' Rebovich said. ''You are claiming
to be this experienced politician who knows how to function in the
Washington D.C. arena. Then how do you misspeak on such an
important issue?''
</P>
<P>
   Florio during the debates did squeeze Corzine into several
corners, most notably getting him to defend the gun industry
Tuesday before an audience of 500 in Livingston, a debate that was
not telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ''While I was taking on the gun lobby, Jon was financing the gun
industry,'' Florio charged.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine replied, ''I hope the governor isn't suggesting we have
a ban on guns, or is he suggesting that Smith &AMP; Wesson and
Remington, who sell guns to our military operations, legally, are
somehow operating outside the law?''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Corzine told the New York Times he would have
opposed financing gun manufacturers had he known about it while at
Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Florio in the debates also pressed Corzine into detailing his
views in support of gay marriage, open enlistment of gays in the
military and a moratorium on all executions because of concerns
over racism in the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   None of those were errors, but they do help Florio -- and any
potential Republican opponents -- put Corzine on the liberal fringe.
Notably, Corzine avoids those issues on his elaborately detailed
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Florio also may have drawn in an unneeded opponent -- his nemesis
of the 1993 election, Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's radio debate, and again Thursday, Florio said racial
profiling by the New Jersey State Police picked up after he had
left office.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a falloff in some of the incidents that were
reported to us, particularly by the ACLU (American Civil Liberties
Union), which was monitoring these things. Then after I left
office, apparently there was a picking up again of this and so when
the United States Justice Department came to New Jersey and
reviewed the records for 10 years back, they concluded there was a
sufficient pattern of this sort of activity from 1995 on, so as to
be able to file complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was out of the country last week but her spokeswoman,
Jayne O'Connor, accused Florio of rewriting history. She said
federal agencies began investigating the State Police after a 1996
state court ruling concerning patrol practices on the New Jersey
Turnpike for several previous years, including the four during
which Florio was governor.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
</TEXT>
