<HEADLINE> Key Players in China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key players in this week House debate on China trade:
President Clinton
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton is making the bill to grant permanent trade benefits to
China a major foreign policy initiative of his final year in
office. He is lobbying energetically down to the wire, inviting
lawmakers to the White House to engage in personal persuasion.
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, DeLay, one of Clinton's most caustic critics and a
leader in the 1999 impeachment effort, has become a principal ally
on the China-trade vote. Delay has become the point man for
rounding up Republican votes. Because far more Republicans are
supporting the legislation than Democrats, Clinton must rely on him
for the bulk of the support.
Reps. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they drafted a bipartisan side agreement designed to
bridge differences and pick up additional support for the China
trade bill. It would create a commission to monitor human rights in
China and set up a mechanism for protecting U.S. businesses from
surges in certain imports from China. Their proposal has been
embraced by both the Clinton administration and Republican leaders,
who plan to incorporate it into the underlying trade bill. Levin is
the senior Democrat on the Ways and Means trade subcommittee and
Bereuter is chairman of the International Relations subcommittee on
Asia.
House Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The top vote-counter among Democrats, Bonior, long a close ally
of organized labor, has been leading the opposition to the bill.
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   As the top Democrat in the House, Gephardt has walked a careful
path in not seeking to make the trade vote a party matter. He
opposes the legislation, but has let others do most of the work in
opposing it. Still, as the senior Democrat, his views carry a lot
of weight among Democrats.
Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With both Gephardt and Bonior opposing the bill, the job of
trying to rally Democratic support has fallen mostly to Matsui, a
leading congressional advocate of expanding international commerce
and improved ties with China. He has been keeping daily of
Democrats on board, a sometimes daunting task.
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As senior Democrat on the House Ways and Means Committee and as
a senior member of the Congressional Black Caucus, Rangel has a lot
of pull among Democrats. A usual ally of organized labor, Rangel
remained on the fence on the trade bill until last week. But his
announcement of support was viewed as instrumental in bringing in
other Democratic votes -- and he is now working actively to try to
pass the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
