<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Thomas To Reduce Speeches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Justice Clarence Thomas says his public
speaking days are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time we open our mouths, we come close to compromising
what we do,'' he told the Richmond Bar Association. Thomas said he
will reduce his speaking schedule and called Friday night's speech
something of ''a last hurrah for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to written questions from the audience, Thomas said
televising the Supreme Court's oral arguments is a bad idea.
''People act strange when a camera is on them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also said he believes his colleagues ask too many
questions during oral arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court was a fairly quiet court when I arrived'' in 1991,
he said. ''Now we look like 'The Family Feud.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said former President George Bush, who appointed him to
the court, recently asked him whether he would again go through the
bruising confirmation process, in which former associate Anita Hill
accused him of sexually harassing her.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, in a heartbeat,'' Thomas said he told Bush. ''I thank God
that I have the opportunity to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
