<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 24 Die as Turkey Boats Capsize  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Two overcrowded fishing boats capsized in
rough waters of the Black Sea on Saturday. At least 24 Turks
drowned, most of them women and children, local authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The boats had set sail from the coastal town of Besikduzu on a
cruise to mark a locally celebrated sea festivity, Gov. Adil Yazar
of the nearby port city Trabzon told private NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen people were injured and hospitalized in Trabzon. The
small boats had been overloaded, Anatolia news agency said. But it
was unclear how many people were aboard, or how many people the
boats could safely hold.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw a huge wave coming toward us, and I jumped into the
sea,'' an unidentified young man who was rescued by local
fishermen, told private CNN-Turk television.
</P>
<P>
   Another survivor, a pregnant woman named Yasemin Parlak, said
from a hospital bed: ''The boat was so crowded.'' She said she had
survived by holding onto the capsized boat. Her 8-month-old baby
also was hospitalized, but Parlak had no news about her husband and
friends who were on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Local fishermen were still searching for survivors hours after
the accident, and a military helicopter from an eastern base
searched the waters from overhead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1401 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MDs Reluctant To Break Bad News  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL Q. HANEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Terminally ill cancer patients rarely get a
straight answer when they ask doctors how long they have to live, a
new survey suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that doctors are likely to be overly
optimistic about their patients' outlooks or simply refuse to say.
Only about one-third are willing to give patients their best guess.
</P>
<P>
   The new research, presented Saturday at the opening of the
annual scientific meeting of the American Society for Clinical
Oncology, suggests that not only are doctors bad at making
predictions, but they are also uncomfortable passing the
information to the people they treat, at least when the message is
discouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elizabeth Lamont of the University of Chicago, one of the
researchers, said the doctors' lack of candor is probably
well-intentioned. They fear the truth may harm their patients,
perhaps by becoming a self-fulfilling prophesy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows a lot of caring and not malice,'' she said. ''They
are genuinely concerned about their patients, is my guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the doctors argue that honesty is probably better for
their patients than a well-meaning falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nicholas Christakis, a co-author of the study, noted that
many patients die in pain, institutionalized and broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''I firmly believe that a lot of these deficits could be
partially addressed if people had access to more reliable
prognostic information,'' he said. ''Part of the reason we die
badly is because we don't see death coming and we don't plan
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Christakis said patients need reliable information so they can
get their finances in order, redo their wills, decide whether to
enter experimental drug studies or ask family members to take time
off from work to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved 258 doctors caring for 326 cancer patients
who were entering five Chicago hospices. When asked by the
researchers, nearly all the doctors were willing to estimate their
patients' survival time. But when asked what they would say if the
patients insisted on knowing these predictions, only about
one-third of the doctors said they would give a truthful answer.
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter said they would refuse to answer at all, saying
something like, ''Only God knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 40 percent said they would give an inaccurate estimate.
Nearly three-quarters of these doctors would sugarcoat the answer,
telling patients they will live longer than they really believe.
The rest would paint a picture even more grim than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Christakis said there are many reasons to avoid a straight
answer, including the sheer unpleasantness of delivering bad news.
However, he said, many ''believe these will be self-fulfilling
prophesies, that bad news can contribute to bad outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Gradishar of Northwestern University, who was not
involved in the research, said the data ''suggest doctors tend to
be overly optimistic. It gets to the difficulty of breaking bad
news, although one would assume that news has already been broken
if people are going into hospices.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, people are admitted to hospice care only if they have
six months or less to live. Christakis said the doctors'
unwillingness to be open with these patients suggests that in
everyday practice, they might be even less willing to tell the
truth than the survey suggests.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier report published in February in the British
Medical Journal, the doctors checked how accurate the doctors'
predictions actually turned out to be. It found they were usually
off target and on average assumed the patients would live five
times longer than they actually did.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Society of Clinical Oncology:
http://www.asco.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1403 </TRAILER>
