<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monitoring Cancer Care Explored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Doctors are examining the possibility of
setting up a nationwide system to monitor the quality of cancer
care.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the annual scientific meeting of the American Society
for Clinical Oncology said Saturday that a pilot study is getting
under way with 600 patients being treated for breast and colon
cancer in Los Angeles, Houston and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers will review patient medical records to assess
the level of care given to each patient, including the kind of
treatment given and the extent of follow-up. Patients also will be
interviewed about their treatment experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the project is to make sure cancer patients
everywhere get the highest quality of care, said Dr. Joseph S.
Bailes, president of the oncology society.
</P>
<P>
   The study will be overseen by doctors from the oncology society,
as well as patient advocates and other health experts, and it will
be conducted by researchers from Harvard University and the RAND
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The study is being financed with a $1 million grant from the
Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation. Doctors said it is a
response to a report from the Institute of Medicine last year that
recommended improving information about the quality of cancer care
nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
