<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Scraps TV China Trade Pitch  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton canceled a nationally
televised speech on behalf of China trade legislation after being
told by congressional Democrats that such a high-profile appeal
actually could cost him support on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We became convinced it would be better to keep the decibel
level low and to work with our undecided members one on one instead
of using the megaphone of television,'' said Tom Keaney, a top aide
to Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., the Democrats' chief vote-counter
on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The president abruptly scrapped Sunday night's five-minute Oval
Office address while he was on a political fund-raising trip to
Philadelphia and Chicago on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We indicated to the White House that a speech at this point
would do more harm than good,'' Keaney said in an interview
Saturday. ''We wanted to keep the noise down. We just felt a speech
would be counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Added White House spokeswoman Jennifer Palmieri: ''They've
advised us that they don't think that the Oval Office address is
the most productive way to get votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton planned to place calls to House
members over the weekend to try to enlist support.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote late Wednesday or on Thursday.
Supporters are claiming momentum and believe they are close to the
218 votes needed for passage. But lawmakers on both sides agreed
the vote could be very close.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would open China's markets to more U.S. goods, and end
20 years of annual reviews of China's trade status. The bill is
supported by the business community and opposed by labor,
environmental and some veterans' groups.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ABC nor CBS planned a live broadcast of the speech. ABC
said the network had covered both sides of the issue on its news
programs, and CBS said the address amounted to lobbying. NBC, CNN
and Fox planned to carry it live.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
