<HEADLINE> Relatives Remember WWII Sub Victims  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAVRATA, Greece (AP) -- A lone bugler played and laurel wreaths
floated over the resting place of a sunken British World War II
submarine as relatives gathered at the spot for the first time
Saturday to pay homage to 60 seamen who perished there almost six
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only one man managed to surface alive from the Ionian Sea depths
in December 1941 after a mine explosion ripped through the H.M.S.
Perseus and sunk the sub. The Perseus lay undisturbed until it was
found by Greek divers two years ago off the coast of Mavrata, a
small village about 120 miles northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives wept as they tossed simple tributes into the sea:
wreaths with notes pinned to them and bottles holding letters. The
bugler ended two minutes of silence with the military score Last
Post.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the most wonderful experience that I've ever had, to pay
tribute to my father and say good-bye,'' said Cynthia Neave, of
Sydney, Australia, daughter of the submarine's captain, Lt. Cmdr.
Edward Nicolay. ''It's the first time I've ever really been able to
cry for my father.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perseus struck a mine and sank on Dec. 9, 1941, while on
patrol off the coast. It lies, tilted slightly on its starboard
side, at a depth of 171 feet. Fifty-nine British seamen and one
Greek officer died.
</P>
<P>
   Stoker John Capes, the only survivor, managed to swim to shore,
where islanders hid him from Italian and later Nazi troops for 18
months before smuggling him to Turkey and freedom. Capes died a
decade ago. But his daughter, Julie Knappett, was in Greece to meet
those he served with and some of the islanders who sheltered him.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I leave here, it's like having to lay my father to rest
again,'' said Knappett, of Suffolk, England. ''Because it's like
the other relatives and those who helped him have resurrected him
again.''
</P>
<P>
   There had always been suspicion about Capes' story -- until Greek
diver Kostas Thoctarides found evidence to back up his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Capes had described how he used an escape mechanism to flood his
compartment and equalize the pressure as the submarine settled on
the seabed. Divers found the hatch open and the bottle of rum that
Capes said he used to boost his courage, along with about three
other stokers who survived the initial explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems the others never managed to leave the compartment.
Thoctarides said he saw human bones, an empty boiler suit and three
boots, indicating at least two people had died there.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 relatives, as well as representatives of the Royal Navy
and the Submariners Association, traveled from Britain and
Australia for the memorial services that began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have gone to the other side of the world for this,''
wept Marienne Haynes, whose brother Claud Francis, 24, died on the
Perseus. ''I could never have missed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
