<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Eritrea on Alert  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- The United States set in motion a partial
evacuation of its embassy here Saturday -- a move that some feared
could be the start of a general foreign pullout from Eritrea's
anxious capital as troops from neighboring Ethiopia advance on the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, pushing to end its two-year-old border war with
Eritrea, claimed to have moved within 60 miles of Asmara. Scattered
charred corpses of Eritrean soldiers and debris of twisted tanks,
spent shells and discarded ammunition lined the routes of the
Ethiopian forces' eight-day-old onslaught. Ethiopia said Eritrean
troops were blowing up bridges to try to slow the advance.
</P>
<P>
   The United States chartered a plane expected to arrive Sunday
for the State Department-ordered evacuation of nonessential embassy
staff and their dependents. Officials encouraged private American
citizens to take the plane out as well.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of expatriates are expected to board the flight. Twelve
embassy workers will remain in the capital, embassy spokeswoman
Collette Christian said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department called for the partial evacuation late
Friday, citing deteriorating security. It is the third time since
the Ethiopian-Eritrean war erupted in May 1998 that nonessential
staff have been withdrawn from the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Because of U.S. influence internationally, the decision has an
impact far beyond the number of evacuees. Relief agencies feared it
would trigger an exodus of aid workers, imperiling desperately
needed aid projects and -- with hundreds of thousands of hungry
Eritreans fleeing the fighting -- even further endangering lives.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats feared other governments would follow
Washington's suit, deepening the sense of international isolation
Eritrea has repeatedly expressed since the invasion began. Eritrean
Presidential spokesman Yemane Gebremeskel insisted that Asmara was
not in danger and accused the U.S. government of failing to speak
out strongly since Ethiopian forces stormed Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lack of a strong U.S. condemnation of the Ethiopian
invasion is disappointing and inexplicable,'' Gebremeskel said.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian troops, artillery and warplanes opened their offensive
May 12, quickly retaking a piece of disputed territory Eritrea
seized in May 1998. Ethiopia denies any intention of taking over
recognized Eritrean territory but has given no sign of stopping its
two-pronged offensive from the north and south.
</P>
<P>
   In military moves Saturday, Ethiopia said its warplanes bombed a
missile base south of Asmara and attacked a major military compound
in the west for a second day.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage of battle and the smell of rotting corpses lined
the road from the Ethiopian border to the southern town of Barentu,
a key post captured Wednesday by Ethiopia. Most of the dead in the
fighting apparently have been buried quickly, in keeping with the
Muslim and local Christian tradition.
</P>
<P>
   At one spot, corpses and parts of corpses surrounded a mauled
Eritrean troop truck that appeared to have taken a direct hit from
a rocket. The burned hands and feet of Eritrean casualties
protruded from a churned patch of bulldozed earth.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia claimed some Eritrean soldiers were retreating into
neighboring Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of the estimated 550,000 Eritreans uprooted by the
fighting also are seeking refuge across the Sudanese border. Most
are women and children, ''streaming in by foot, by donkey and by
truck,'' Lindsey Davies of the U.N. World Food Program said
Saturday. Aid agencies estimated 12,250 had fled into Sudan at
three crossings in recent days, Davies said in the Kenyan capital,
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Christian said no Americans in Asmara were in imminent danger.
Still, she said, ''It would be imprudent to wait longer to get
nonessential staff out.'' There are roughly 300 U.S. citizens and
green-card holders in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Germany and the Netherlands also have encouraged their citizens
to leave, and Germany was readying contingency plans to evacuate
its embassy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
