<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harlem residents pleased that Giuliani is out of the race  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani reincarnated as a
softhearted, sensitive guy?
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced.
</P>
<P>
   A day after a newly introspective Giuliani dropped his Senate
bid, some black and Hispanic New Yorkers cheered the withdrawal and
questioned the sincerity of the mayor's promise to try to heal the
city's racial divides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hallelujah!'' shouted one man at a Harlem rally led by the
Rev. Al Sharpton. ''Hallelujah!''
</P>
<P>
   His exuberance spoke volumes about the tension that has long
characterized the combative mayor's relationships with many of the
city's minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't wish ill health on anybody, but I will not forget the
tears that you ignored,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's emotional announcement that prostate cancer would
force him to forego the race against first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton included some reflections on his strained relations with
many black and Hispanic New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would consider changing the way he approached some
issues and spoke of overcoming ''barriers that maybe I placed
there. ... I'm going to try to reach out to more people, and to try
and help more people.''
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting the night before he dropped out, Giuliani
said he regretted the way he'd handled the police shooting of
Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed black man. Giuliani was widely
criticized for releasing Dorismond's sealed juvenile police record
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd done right in releasing the records, but admitted
he should have been more understanding with regard to the loss of a
person's life.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the apology didn't go far enough, and Dorismond's
sister, Maria Dorismond, said, ''It's too late, don't come to us
with this story.''
</P>
<P>
   Some were more willing to temper their ill feelings toward
Giuliani in light of his cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course I feel bad for him, but what goes around comes
around. You ever hear of karma?'' said Joseph Taylor, 22, as he
rushed to get out of the rain on 125th Street.
</P>
<P>
   But others could not put aside their anger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I should feel bad for him, but what kind of
compassion has he ever shown,'' said Michaela Harrison, a New York
University graduate student, while leaving the subway station at
St. Nicholas Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel (D-Harlem), on the other hand, said
that while he thinks the mayor did the right thing in dropping out,
he wishes him well.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton noted that since Giuliani was no longer in the race,
Clinton could no longer expect the voting landscape to remain the
same and warned that the mayor's absence from the race means she
can no longer take the votes of anti-Giuliani minorities for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I predict that had Giuliani stayed in the race there would
have been a record turnout of blacks and Latinos to vote against
him. ... Now that he is removed, Mrs. Clinton has to give us a
reason to come out to vote for her,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton ought to take this as a signal not to ignore our
community,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 1549 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
