<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Senator Blocks U.N. Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a foreign policy dispute with the Clinton
administration, a Republican senator who oversees State Department
spending is blocking the government from paying $368 million owed
to the United Nations for four peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., believes it is unfair for U.S.
taxpayers to pay for part of the U.N. operations in Congo, Kosovo,
East Timor and Sierra Leone, a spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The money originally was intended for other purposes by the
State Department, but later was set aside to help pay for the
peacekeeping efforts and therefore required Gregg's approval,
Edmund Amorosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, chairman of the Senate Appropriations subcommittee that
handles spending for the Commerce, Justice and State departments,
has said he would keep the money on hold until, at the least, the
situation in Sierra Leone had changed.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Saturday referred questions about Gregg's
move to the State Department. A State Department spokeswoman
declined to address Gregg's action, instead citing remarks
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright made last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Wednesday at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, she said
that ''legislators who are denying funds for U.N. missions in
Kosovo, East Timor, the Congo and Sierra Leone are making a grave
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Troublemakers in these regions cannot simply be wished away,
they must be contained, captured, convicted or converted which, in
every case, requires resources,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's spokesman said the senator ''feels the United States
needs to be engaged in world affairs, but these particular
instances, he disagrees with the Clinton administration's policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Amorosi cited Sierra Leone specifically as a peacekeeping effort
''gone awry.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 330 U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone, which has been
torn apart by civil war, have been held hostage by rebel leaders
for nearly three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg is angry about the Clinton administration's role in
encouraging a peace agreement signed in July that gave amnesty and
a share or power to the rebel leader Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's rebels have been accused of the rape, murder and
mutilation of thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, Gregg said he soon hoped to see the
establishment of a war crimes tribunal similar to what was set up
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest in a tiff between Republicans and the
Clinton administration over the United States' role in
international peacekeeping operations. Of late, senators from both
parties have been voicing concern over America's role in overseas
peacekeeping efforts, specifically Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. John Warner, R-Va. and Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., had drawn up
a measure which proposed the establishment of a deadline for the
removal of U.S. troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was narrowly defeated by the Senate on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
