<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Montclair teens accused of buying guns online  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTCLAIR, N.J. (AP) -- Two teen-agers faked a federal gun
license and bought semiautomatic handguns over the Internet from a
gun dealer, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the 17-year-old boys, both students at Montclair
High School, had purchased at least eight handguns online from a
Texas-based gun distributor since March. They also said the pair
may have placed orders for up to 20 more pistols, but did not
receive them, over a longer time.
</P>
<P>
   Local and state police and federal officials found several fake
firearms licenses and three loaded, 9 mm semiautomatic Glock
pistols after raiding one of the boys' homes. Two other handguns
that had been paid for had not yet been delivered to the home, the
address for a bogus company called ''Clint's Guns Distributors,''
said Montclair Police Chief Thomas Russo.
</P>
<P>
   He said it appeared the boys' parents were unaware of their gun
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The raid happened Tuesday after authorities set up a
''controlled delivery.'' A postal inspector posing as a United
Parcel Service worker delivered a handgun to one of the teens.
Authorities said they descended on the house with a search warrant
after seeing one of the boys sign for the package. They used a
battering ram to smash open the door after the teen refused to open
it.
</P>
<P>
   Police said besides the guns and the bogus licenses, they seized
a personal computer used to make the gun purchases. The State
Police High Tech Unit was looking through the computer for evidence
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The second teen's home was searched after the afternoon raid.
</P>
<P>
   Russo said authorities were still looking for three other
handguns and 90 rounds of ammunition. A Thursday afternoon
locker-by-locker search with the help of police dogs at Montclair
High School -- requested by school officials -- turned up no weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The high school seniors were held Tuesday night in the Essex
County Youth House and were charged with conspiracy, three counts
of forgery and three counts of unlawful possession of a weapon. The
juveniles, whose names were withheld because of their ages, later
were released to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The youths also could face federal charges. The Essex County
Prosecutor's Office was still deciding whether to try the teens as
adults, said Chief Assistant Prosecutor Norman Menz.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they didn't know why the boys were buying the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't predict what these kids were going to do with these
guns,'' Russo told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Saturday's
editions. ''But certainly at least a tragedy has been averted here,
be it hurting themselves or others, or even in the commission of a
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Classmates said the pair, who have been suspended from school,
are former football players who like to sometimes play the role of
class clown.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're two of the funniest guys you'll ever know,'' Terah
Johnson, a senior at the high school, told The Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the pair apparently had caused no trouble in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ''To my knowledge, they were never problem students,'' Russo
said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper cited two unnamed sources in saying the boys began
their gun-dealing after posing as adults in an Internet chat room
and asking a Florida gun dealer for advice on how they could open
their own gunshop. The dealer sent the pair a copy of his license
and the teens copied that license, forming the bogus company, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear how authorities uncovered the boys' activities.
</P>
<P>
   Russo said a UPS worker alerted authorities after becoming
suspicious of a package bearing the name of a gun company being
delivered to a residential address.
</P>
<P>
   But according to another account, a package in transit opened
during handling and was sent back to the Texas distributor. The
distributor notified federal authorities after seeing the New
Jersey address and the Florida gun license, said Tony Esposito, a
spokesman for the U.S. Postal Inspection Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
