<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Accused of Slaughter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Congolese rebels massacred more than 300
people in a village in eastern Congo, hacking many of the victims
to death before throwing them in a river, a Rome-based missionary
news agency reported Saturday. Rebels denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   The MISNA agency, citing unidentified sources, said the
Rwandan-backed rebels of the Congolese Rally for Democracy last
week attacked Katogota, 35 miles south of the Lake Kivu port of
Bukavu.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of the report. The news
agency said that, in general, it draws its reports in developing
countries from lay people and officials, as well as missionaries.
But it does not identify sources it thinks might be put in danger.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the rebels have accused the missionary news agency
of inflating the casualties in the civil war and spreading
anti-rebel feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Kin-Kiey Mulumba said that in this case, most of
the villagers had fled Katogota and no civilian casualties occurred
when rebels attacked in retaliation for the death of one of their
commanders. The commander was killed in an ambush in the village by
a pro-government militia, Mulumba said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their count is surrealist,'' Mulumba said by telephone from
the eastern rebel stronghold of Goma. ''We've launched our own
inquiry into this incident, and we'll investigate. Anyone else,
including the United Nations, is free to join.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been fighting for more than a year to oust
President Laurent Kabila. They are unpopular in eastern Congo,
where the war-wearied population regard them as accomplices of
their foreign backers, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the New York-based Human Rights Watch accused
the rebels and their Rwandan army allies of raping and killing
civilians to punish them for allegedly supporting their enemies,
the Rwandan Hutu militiamen and pro-government forces. Mulumba on
Friday denied those accusations and invited the United Nations to
investigate any human rights abuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
