<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collapse won't affect Penn's Landing development  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The deadly collapse of a wooden pier within
walking distance of Penn's Landing on Thursday will not affect the
construction timetable of a $190 million entertainment and retail
complex on the Philadelphia waterfront, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After years of delay, construction at Penn's Landing is finally
set to begin in August or September. Opening is slated for fall
2002. With cities like Baltimore and New York having so much
success attracting visitors to their own redeveloped waterfronts,
Philadelphia has a lot riding on its ambitious project.
</P>
<P>
   The pier collapse ''wouldn't appear to have any effect on our
development plans,'' said Billie Scott, a spokeswoman for Simon
Property Group Inc., the Indianapolis-based developer.
</P>
<P>
   Three women -- all employees of the New Jersey State Aquarium in
Camden, N.J. -- were killed and 37 were injured Thursday night when
the pier, which supported a new outdoor nightclub called Heat,
collapsed into the murky waters of the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were still trying to determine a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another 20-foot by 15-foot section of the pier
collapsed Saturday morning into the Delaware River, said police
spokesman Corp. Jim Pauley. No one was injured, but divers
searching the river were pulled out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   The three women killed were among six aquarium employees
celebrating the birthday of DeAnn White, the aquarium's public
relations manager. A resident of Philadelphia's Germantown section,
she would have turned 26 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Ferraro, 27, of Cherry Hill, was an eight-year employee at
the aquarium and had recently been promoted to marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Rodriguez, 22, had just finished the first day at her new
job. Rodriguez, also of Cherry Hill, had been hired as a special
events assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other three workers attending were injured.
</P>
<P>
   A number of restaurants and nightclubs catering to the
college-age crowd sit on the waterfront's ''finger'' piers -- some
believed to be 100 years old -- in the former industrial area. Mayor
John F. Street has ordered inspections for all of them and will
talk with engineers and other officials on establishing a regular
inspection, maintenance and certification process.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a tragic incident,'' Street said after touring the
scene of the accident on a Coast Guard utility boat in the pouring
rain on a cold, gray Saturday afternoon. ''We will do everything we
can to see to it that nothing like this ever happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Street says he plans to discuss with engineers how such
inspections should take place and how often. In the meantime, he
said a visual inspection Friday of the buildings on all city piers
found no evidence that any others are unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very, very busy time at Penn's Landing and on our
waterfront and we just want people to feel absolutely, 100 percent
secure in using (these) facilities,'' Street said.
</P>
<P>
   Club owners, however, maintain they are completely safe. Clark
Mahoney, general manager of Rock Lobster, said the nightclub's pier
is inspected every year and can ''easily accommodate our current
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Batt, executive director of the Waterfront Business
Association, said other businesses on the piers are likewise
diligent about inspections. None are planning to close pending the
safety review, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not think it will have a great negative impact'' on
business, Batt said.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people who will be affected will be some of the club
owners and some of the more temporary club structures,'' said Meryl
Levitz, head of the Greater Philadelphia Tourism Marketing Corp.
''Local people might have second thoughts about that, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The piers originally supported warehouses but were converted
into restaurants and clubs in the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake on the project, officials sought to
distance the complex -- only three decades old -- from its neighbors.
Most of Penn's Landing sits on dry land, with only a small portion
jutting out into the water, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been getting the message out that this is an entirely
different situation and they should not have any concerns about the
safety of Penn's Landing,'' said Dominic Sabatini, president of the
Penn's Landing Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the Simon Group spokeswoman, said she would be more
worried about visitors' perceptions of the waterfront's safety if
the complex was opening sooner than it is.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were open and operating or scheduled to open in the very
near future, anyone would have cause for concern about
perception,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded Penn's Landing will be three times larger than
Baltimore's glittery Inner Harbor and feature a 30,0000-square-foot
FAO Schwarz store and other retailers, a children's museum, upscale
restaurants, an amphitheater, movie theaters and an aerial tram
over the Delaware to Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope the project will breathe new life into the area
where William Penn first set foot in Philadelphia in 1682.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 1645 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haiti Prepares For Elections  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE FAUL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Torn between fears of violence and
a burning desire to change their lives, Haitians have a chance to
choose a new Parliament on Sunday in long-delayed elections that
would restore a legal government and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   But a flare-up of political violence, government foot-dragging
and bumbling preparations could mean trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know everyone says there's going to be violence, and not to
go out and vote, but I'm going no matter what,'' said 30-year-old
mason Jesuslhomme Guerrier. ''I'm not going to let the macoutes
(bandits) run our country again.''
</P>
<P>
   Haitians who have largely boycotted an electoral process fraught
with fraud and disorganization over recent years have registered to
vote en masse, some 4 million of the 8 million people in a country
where half the population is under 18.
</P>
<P>
   But many voters' enthusiasm has been doused by fear and more
than a dozen assassinations that prompted opposition candidates to
stop campaigning. The United States and United Nations -- which
intervened to restore democracy in 1994 -- worry their experiment to
instill democracy in this Caribbean nation is unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   ''By turning out to register in large numbers, Haitians have
demonstrated their commitment ... to the democratic process,'' U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's turnout will show whether Haitians can overcome their
fears.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning ended on a dull note Friday, with just 200 people
showing up for a rally of former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide's
Lavalas Family in the seaside shantytown of Cite Soleil, a party
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties say the elections are being rigged to favor
Lavalas and set up a dictatorship under the populist Aristide, who
few doubt will win presidential elections planned for November.
</P>
<P>
   Overthrown in a 1991 coup, Aristide was restored to power after
the 1994 invasion. Barred by law from seeking a consecutive term,
he picked Rene Preval to succeed him in 1995 elections that brought
Haiti's first democratic handover of power.
</P>
<P>
   Preval created an unconstitutional government by disbanding
Parliament in 1999 and appointing a new premier by decree.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's elections -- postponed at least four times since 1998 --
give Haitians a chance to right things and, in the process, free
$500 million in foreign aid desperately needed in a country where
65 percent of the work force is unemployed, average annual income
is less then $350 and 80 percent of children go to bed hungry.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also will test Aristide's ability to stock Parliament
and thousands of local government offices with Lavalas loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Haiti's U.N.-trained police force has been unable --
or unwilling -- to stop pre-election violence, and only 3,500
officers will police Sunday's balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Short of a miracle, I don't see how we can have credible
elections,'' opposition politician Evans Paul said after a grenade
exploded Thursday at the gate to the electoral council office,
injuring seven passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, he said, was intended ''to intimidate the
independent voter into staying at home, leaving the field wide open
for Aristide partisans.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavalas Family spokesmen routinely deny the party is behind the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   From afar, the United States and the United Nations -- which have
invested more than $1 billion in Haiti since the 1994 intervention
-- are keeping their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite all the difficulties observed, credible legislative,
municipal and local elections are still possible,'' the
Organization of American States said Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1649 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0086 </DOCNO>
