<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 22-year-old gets 25 years in prison for 1998 shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y.(AP) -- A white man who shot a black woman in what
one prosecutor described as a ''human hunting trip'' into a
predominantly black neighborhood was sentenced Friday to the
maximum of 25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In December of 1998, Rudolf Berry and his friend William Hines,
both of the Schenectady County town of Rotterdam, traveled into
Albany, about 11 miles away. Berry shot a 9-mm rifle from the car
as Hines allegedly drove, wounding 39-year-old Sonya Thompson of
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   After their arrests, police said the men confessed to traveling
to Albany specifically to shoot a black person.
</P>
<P>
   But in his statement to police, Berry said he just wanted fire
the gun out the car window and wake people up. He said he didn't
see Thompson when he fired the shot.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government didn't pursue hate crimes against the two
because an FBI probe didn't find enough evidence of federal hate
crimes violations.
</P>
<P>
   County Judge Thomas A. Breslin chastised Berry for getting
''loaded on booze and marijuana'' and ''when that wasn't
enough...to drive to this community and level a gun out a window
and shoot someone is just preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines' trial has yet to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was treated and released from Albany Medical Center
Hospital shortly after being struck in the right front side of her
neck by a slug from a 9 mm rifle.
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing, she urged Berry to do some ''conscientious
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am angry and hurt, but I'm not prejudiced, so I hope you get
the help that is needed,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
