<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prisoner Abuse Indictment Dismissed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A federal judge has dismissed a criminal
indictment against a former sheriff's deputy accused of letting a
dog bite a prisoner during a videotaped jail shakedown in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sam Kent granted the dismissal Friday at the
request of U.S. attorneys who failed to convince 10 of 12 jurors in
October that dog-handler David Cisneros committed a felony civil
rights violation against inmate Toby Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kent nor prosecutors explained the dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne and dozens of other Missouri prison inmates were
housed in the Brazoria County Jail, where the shakedown occurred,
under a contract with a private corrections firm.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the video, ostensibly made for training purposes,
Missouri canceled its contract and moved its prisoners out of
Texas. The tape showed prisoners being electrically jolted and
kicked.
</P>
<P>
   ttorney Guy Womack said Cisneros, who faced up to 10 years in
prison, was relieved the case had been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bite was never intentional,'' Womack said. ''You can tell
very clearly from the videotape that David was pulling back on the
leash, trying to stop the dog from even nipping the inmate.''
</P>
<P>
   Two former guards were sentenced earlier this year for their
roles in the incident. Wilton David Wallace was sentenced to four
years for kicking Hawthorne and injuring another inmate. Lester
Arnold received a one-year sentence for using a stun gun on
Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   Also in January, a federal judge approved a $2.2 million
settlement in a class-action case brought by Missouri inmates who
claimed they were abused while housed in Texas jails. The lawsuit
was sparked by the videotape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1718 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 28 Officers Implicated in LAPD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Prosecutors have turned over to defense
lawyers the names of 28 officers implicated in a police corruption
scandal, along with transcripts of interviews with the disgraced
officer whose allegations led to the dismissal of dozens of
convictions, the Los Angeles Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The officers are suspected of misconduct ranging from planting
evidence to unjustified shootings, the newspaper said. Four of the
28 remain on active duty, three of them at the Rampart Division
that is at the heart of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is a strong suspicion that they have been engaged in
misconduct, they should be placed on administrative leave
immediately,'' said Public Defender Michael Judge.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. David Kalish, a police spokesman, declined to comment to
the Times on why the officers were still working. Kalish did not
immediately return a phone call Saturday from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Sandi Gibbons, a spokeswoman for the district attorney's office,
said Saturday that information had been turned over to the public
defender, but she was unable to confirm how many officers' names
were presented.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office will present more names as early
as this week, spokeswoman Victoria Pipkin said. ''This was just the
beginning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Following days of negotiations, District Attorney Gil Garcetti
on Friday turned over 3,242 pages of transcribed interviews to the
defender lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The had been seeking the information since the scandal broke in
September. Allegations by former officer Rafael Perez that
anti-gang officers in the Rampart area lied in court and framed
suspects have led to the dismissal of more than 80 criminal
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt we should have had this information a long time ago,''
Judge said. ''The failure to disclose this information has
significantly impeded our ability to identify the cases that
warrant reopening, as well as to successfully defend innocent
people charged in current cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys received the Perez transcripts and other
information under an agreement that bars them from revealing it on
threat of contempt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
