<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio says he will run against Hillary Clinton for Senate  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ISLIP, N.Y. (AP) -- U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, standing in his
high school gym, announced plans Saturday for the run of his life --
a Senate campaign that pits the unknown Long Island Republican
against first lady Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can tell from my accent that I am a lifelong New Yorker,''
said Lazio, who ran track at West Islip High School before
graduating in 1976. ''I don't have to fake it. ... I've never
needed an exploratory committee to help me figure out where I
wanted to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement, coming less than 24 hours after New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani dropped out of the Senate race,
catapulted Lazio from semi-obscurity into the national spotlight in
the year's most talked-about political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The location was selected to emphasize Lazio's New York roots, a
contrast with Democratic candidate Clinton. The first lady moved
into Westchester County just five months ago after declaring her
intention to seek retiring U.S. Senator Daniel Moynihan's seat.
</P>
<P>
   The four-term Congressman acknowledged facing an uphill battle
against the high-profile first lady -- one poll already showed her
with a huge lead over Lazio. But he sounded an optimistic note to
supporters who sported T-shirts reading, ''Lazio -- Made in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Here in New York, we love underdogs,'' Lazio told the cheering
crowd. ''... I can't call on Air Force One whenever I need a ride,
but New Yorkers can count on me and call on me whenever they need
something to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's announcement had a small-town feel, with red, white and
blue balloons inside the gym. The crowd cheered wildly throughout
the speech by the boyish-looking Lazio, a local boy made good.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who had asked Lazio to step aside in
Giuliani's favor last year, said the congressman will be a
formidable opponent for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio has the ideas, the energy and the vision to beat
Hillary Clinton in November,'' Pataki said in a press release. ''I
know he will be an effective fighter for all of us as our next
senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged Lazio's entrance to the race during a stop
Saturday in Mt. Kisco, N.Y. at a Boys and Girls Club award
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to welcome to Congressman Lazio into the race for
the Senate. I'm looking forward to a real discussion with him of
the issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, top Clinton adviser Harold Ickes branded the
42-year-old Lazio as a puppet of ''Newt Gingrich and (House
majority leader) Dick Armey and the rest of the radical Republican
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a lifelong resident of Long Island, wasted little time in
shooting back Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opponent is a liberal and a proud one, and I respect her
for that,'' Lazio said. 'But make no mistake, she is no more a new
Democrat than she is a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, fellow Long Island congressman Peter King
backed off plans to challenge Lazio for the nomination and instead
endorsed his Republican colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to name recognition, Lazio starts the race short of
Clinton in fund-raising. Lazio has raised $3.5 million, compared to
$12 million for the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, under campaign finance laws, that Lazio could
receive an infusion of cash from the Giuliani campaign's $20
million warchest.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has earned a reputation as an energetic lawmaker, despite
being largely unknown and untested outside his Suffolk County
district.
</P>
<P>
   He is a pro-death penalty Roman Catholic and while he supports
abortion rights generally, he opposes Medicaid funding and
''partial birth'' abortions, which makes him palatable to the
party's more conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   He boasts a strong environmental record, supports gun control
measures and is fiscally conservative. Asked by Republican House
leaders this year to take the lead on a minimum wage increase,
Lazio pushed to include tax breaks for businesses that made the
package acceptable to his more conservative GOP colleagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
