<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Ahead of Israeli Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Fighting has intensified seven weeks
ahead of Israel's troop withdrawal deadline, with Israeli warplanes
blasting southern and eastern Lebanon on Saturday and guerrilla
shelling causing power outages in Israeli border communities.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's air force struck suspected guerrilla infiltration
trails at four different locations along the front line, as
guerrillas -- who have pledged to drive the Israelis out in
humiliation -- launched a series of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jets also struck deep inside Lebanon, targeting a base for
Syrian-backed radical Palestinian guerrillas near the Syrian
border, Lebanese and Israeli officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent word on casualties from Saturday's
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army said it destroyed 10 tanks belonging to the
radical Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command in a raid on the rebel group's Bekaa Valley base. Lebanese
radio said at least three guerrillas died, but security officials
could not confirm the reports.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the guerrilla group, which
opposes Palestinian peace deals with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said an Israeli naval gunboat was firing shells
Saturday evening, as Israeli and allied militia forces returned
fire on guerrillas attacking an outpost manned by the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army. Israel confirmed the fighting
near the Mediterranean coast about 3 miles north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Guerillas attacked the SLA's hilltop outpost at Hardoun,
launching rocket-propelled grenades and firing machine guns while
senior commanders were inspecting the outpost. The militia fought
back, causing some guerrilla casualties, SLA officials said. No SLA
fighters were hurt in the attack, they said.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli military statement in Jerusalem said that, during the
fighting over Hardoun, Israeli fighter jets attacked suspected
guerrilla targets in a nearby valley.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli jets also fired missiles near the front line village of
Arab Salim. Earlier, jets struck near the market town of Nabatiyeh
inland and in the Iqlim al-Tuffah highlands, Lebanese security
officials in the south said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the air raids, the Iran-backed Hezbollah said its
guerrillas opened fire late Saturday at the Israeli military
outpost in Abbad, 500 yards from the border, while Israeli forces
were dismantling equipment. The guerillas, it said, scored
''confirmed hits.''
</P>
<P>
   One shell hit an electricity pole in the area, knocking out
power in the Upper Galilee border towns of Manara, Misgav Am, and
Margaliot, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's air raids were the latest in a series against
suspected guerrilla bases, as Israeli troops dismantled or blew up
outposts in their withdrawal from southern Lebanon ahead of a July
7 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerillas recently have attacked 11 Israeli and allied
militia outposts in the occupied zone, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lebanon accused retreating Israeli troops of planning
to blow up a strategic mountaintop Crusader-era castle that they
are set to abandon. Sitting 2,362 feet high, Beaufort Castle has a
commanding view of areas of southern Lebanon and northern Israel.
The fort is already in ruins from past fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and French governments, which contacted Israel, assured
Beirut that the 12th-century castle would not be destroyed,
according to Prime Minister Salim Hoss' office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1732 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
