<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Vote Violence Is Expected  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Elections Zimbabwe-style have never been
free of violence and intimidation -- it's only the scale that has
differed, participants say.
</P>
<P>
   Violence and punitive attacks around elections in areas where
opposition candidates show strength has been the norm since the
nation's first all-race elections in 1979 that led to independence
from Britain. But this time, it's worse.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe, the country's single ruler since
independence, has called elections for June 24-25. The poll signals
the biggest challenge yet to his two-decade hold on power because
of the emergence of a strong challenger -- the labor-backed Movement
for Democratic Change party.
</P>
<P>
   And already the killing has begun.
</P>
<P>
   At least 23 government opponents have died in political violence
since the government lost a constitutional referendum in February --
its biggest defeat at the polls since independence.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of others have been assaulted or had their rural homes
torched, mainly by ruling party supporters, the main opposition
party has alleged. Many have fled to towns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are now seeing far greater violence to scare the new
opposition,'' said Masipula Sithole, an opposition candidate in the
last parliamentary elections in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sithole, a political scientist at Harare's University of
Zimbabwe, ran for the small Zimbabwe Unity Movement, which failed
to win any seats in the 120 elected constituencies. ZUM attracted
less than 5 percent of ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to that poll, Sithole received death threats from
anonymous callers and suspected ruling party militants failed in a
bid to firebomb his car, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were a small, alternative voice. We were of little
consequence but we were still seen as daring to oppose Mugabe and
that made us his enemy, one to be crushed,'' Sithole said.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's first response to the Movement for Democratic Change
was to crack down, using ruling party militants and veterans of the
1970s liberation war against white rule to assault opposition
supporters and their backers, including white farmers, Sithole
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mobs of squatters and ruling party militants have illegally and
violently staked claims to land on more than 1,200 white-owned
farms in recent months, demanding that farmers withdraw their
support for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, another 13 white-owned farms have been occupied,
the Commercial Farmers Union said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Dongo, who also stood against the ruling party in the
last 1995 parliamentary poll, won her seat as one of three
opposition lawmakers only after the High Court ruled voting was
rigged in her area.
</P>
<P>
   Ballot boxes had been stuffed with more pro-Mugabe votes than
the number of voters registered in Dongo's constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Dongo had also received threats. A firebomb was hurled at her
home. Her supporters were beaten and hounded by the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union Patriotic Front, or ZANU PF, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ZANU PF's way of campaigning. It hasn't changed except we
are seeing more violence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   MDC leader Morgan Tsvangirai said his party was urging
supporters to discard party T-shirts and membership cards to
protect themselves from assailants who search for opposition
materials, often in house-to-house raids late at night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Intimidation is so massive we advise our members to avoid
openly showing they are for MDC,'' Tsvangirai said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning Zimbabwe-style has usually been accompanied by
punitive attacks and recrimination after polling results have gone
against candidates favored by Mugabe, said Sithole, the former
opposition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, he believes, voters won't be fazed by those
memories.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can abuse people only so far. I think Zimbabweans have
been pushed across the line,'' he said. ''There's no coming back to
subservience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
