<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers Seek Delay in Border Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Attorneys for Ahmed Ressam, an Algerian accused
of smuggling explosives into Washington state from Canada, have
asked a federal judge for more time to prepare their case.
</P>
<P>
   Trial is scheduled to begin July 10 in Los Angeles, but Ressam's
public defenders asked for a delay until February.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed in federal court Friday, they told U.S. District
Judge John Coughenour they needed more time to review thousands of
documents and the evidence prosecutors have gathered in their case
against the 32-year-old Ressam.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments on the motion were set for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Diskin, head of the prosecution team, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Coughenour in March granted a defense request to move the trial
to Los Angeles because of extensive publicity about the case in the
Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was arrested Dec. 14 at the U.S.-Canadian border station
at Port Angeles as he tried to enter the country on a ferry.
Customs inspectors said they found bomb-making materials and four
timing devices in the spare-tire compartment of his rental car.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted Ressam on nine counts, including
conspiracy to commit a terrorist act in the United States. If
convicted of all counts, Ressam could face more than 90 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say the arrest exposed an international
terrorist plot that has resulted in three other arrests in
Washington, Montreal and New York. The government has also offered
a $5 million reward for 31-year-old Abdelmajid Dahoumane, another
Algerian who authorities say was staying with Ressam in Canada just
before the arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
