<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reputed mob associate's tip leads to body beneath basement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Federal investigators have found the corpse
of a man buried for at least 25 years beneath the basement of a
building where reputed mob associate Pete ''The Crumb'' Caprio once
ran a social club.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Caprio, who has become a cooperating witness
since he was charged in March with helping in two gangland
executions, tipped them off to the body under the three-story
building on Hudson Street.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators on Tuesday left mounds of dirt behind the sealed
building after the search for the remains of a man known only as
''Butch,'' according to a report in Saturday's editions of The
Star-Ledger of Newark. City records indicated the building belongs
to Caprio's brother, Alphonse.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Caroll, an FBI spokeswoman, confirmed only that a search
warrant had been executed at the building. She said recent
developments in the case kept her from making any additional
comments.
</P>
<P>
   But The Star-Ledger cited unidentified sources in reporting
Caprio had implicated two mob figures in that killing. The sources
also told the newspaper the people implicated had been dead for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   Observers have said the 70-year-old Caprio could be used to
build a federal racketeering case against Joseph ''Skinny Joey''
Merlino, of Philadelphia, and 10 others. Merlino is the reputed
boss of the Bruno organized crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government's case has been reinforced with the help
of another gangland turncoat, former Bruno boss Ralph Natale,
observers said Caprio could give investigators an idea of the
family's hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   It's also likely Caprio would be able to talk about the
influence of the family's Philadelphia mob bosses over activities
in northern New Jersey such as gambling, loansharking and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Caprio was indicted in March on charges he participated in the
1996 murder of reputed Bruno organized crime family captain Joseph
Sodano and the 1994 death of William ''Crazy Willie'' Gantz. Gantz
was reported to be Sodano's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have theorized Sodano was killed after he refused
to give Natale and Merlino a bigger cut of profits from illegal
gambling and loansharking operations in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said Caprio participated in the murders with
others ''for the purpose of maintaining and increasing their
position in the North Jersey crew of the Bruno crime family.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert Sarcone, who represented Caprio at arraignment,
has said his client wasn't the shooter. No others have been
arrested in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
