<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru President, Opponent Trade Barbs  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- In what may be the closest Peru comes to
holding a presidential debate, President Alberto Fujimori traded
barbs with upstart challenger Alejandro Toledo in back-to-back
radio interviews on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori accused Toledo of confusing voters and attempting to
destabilize Peru by calling for a general boycott of the May 28
runoff without officially withdrawing from the race.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated that the vote would not be postponed, despite
mounting international pressure following an April 9 first-round
ballot marred by accusations of vote tampering and dirty tricks by
government forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''A clean election is my responsibility,'' Fujimori said during
a 45-minute interview on Radio Programas del Peru.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Organization of American States, the U.S. State
Department, and Toledo were not qualified to dictate a delay in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour before Fujimori's interview, Toledo was on the same
station saying he would not participate in the scheduled vote. But
he said his party would continue campaigning ''against fraud and
seeking a new, reasonable date to allow the introduction of changes
for a clean election.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for a presidential debate were set to resume last
week, but fell by the wayside Thursday when the National Election
Board rejected Toledo's demand to push the runoff date back to June
18.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, the OAS election delegation had also requested a
postponement, warning that it could not endorse the May 28 ballot
because there was insufficient time to test new vote-counting
software.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman said Friday that Washington
supported the OAS request for a delay, and regretted Toledo's
decision to withdraw, as well as the election board's ''hasty
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said tabulating the upcoming vote would require little
more than a hand calculator because it only involved two
presidential candidates. The April 9 general election included nine
presidential hopefuls, as well as their congressional slates, for a
total of 1,627 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The second round was set after Fujimori narrowly missed a
majority of votes necessary to claim an unprecedented third
five-year term. The final results showed that about 1 million more
ballots were cast than there were voters.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he planned to mobilize peaceful demonstrations
across the nation to pressure Fujimori into changing the date.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Toledo and Fujimori tied in voter preference. Tens of
thousands of people have rallied for both candidates, producing
several violent confrontations in recent days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
