<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deluge of Polls Expected in Future  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The public will be inundated in the coming
months with political polls, some of which might make the
presidential campaign even tougher to understand, says a veteran
pollster, who partly blames the Monica Lewinsky scandal and the
24-hour news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear that the shorter news cycle and the demand for
content'' are having a dramatic effect on the polling industry,
said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for People
and the Press. ''Polls are being ordered up more quickly, being
done more quickly and they're being reported more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken over several days with thorough efforts to reach
possible respondents is more likely to give significant results
than a one-night poll produced under deadline pressure. Kohut
talked about the issue this weekend during the annual meeting of
the American Association for Public Opinion Research.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Kohut cited an overnight poll done immediately
after Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., won the GOP primary in New
Hampshire. The poll that showed McCain essentially even with George
W. Bush in crucial South Carolina, site of the next contested
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut said the poll ''created this notion'' that McCain was a
contender in an extremely tight race in South Carolina. Later polls
showed that the Texas governor held a comfortable lead in the
state, which he won easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''These polls conducted at breakneck speed on the heels of big
events where public opinion is distorted by the emotion of the
moment'' don't really inform the public, Kohut said. ''They are
used as a basis to underscore the narrative of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters Gary Langer of ABC News and Kathleen Frankovic of CBS
News said that polling quickly after big events was often essential
for news operations. They agreed that their responsibility is to
continue polling in subsequent days and put the story in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut noted that public opinion during President Clinton's
impeachment scandal was pretty firm -- that the president should not
be removed from office. But the presidential race this year is
likely to be different, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to see that in 2000,'' he said of the
consistency of polls on impeachment. ''We're going to see lots of
polls at right angles to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Traugott, outgoing president of the pollsters' group,
called on his colleagues to establish more training for journalists
to reduce misinterpretation of polls in the media. This would
include holding more training panels for journalists and providing
contacts who could help reporters interpret poll data.
</P>
<P>
   The effort would expand on educational efforts by another
polling group, the National Council on Public Polls, which produced
a pamphlet outlining the questions a journalist should ask when
writing about a poll.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Web site for the National Council on Public
Polls is www.ncpp.org
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for the American Association for Public Opinion
Research is www.aapor.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1821 </TRAILER>
