<DOCNO> APW20000520.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts focus on causes, cures for AIDS in black communities  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Stigma preventing frank discussion and
underfunded prevention programs are the main reasons AIDS continues
to infect African-Americans at epidemic levels, experts at a
three-day summit in Short Hills concluded Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of government and medical officials, politicians, clergy
and community activists who attended ''An Honest Perspective on
HIV/AIDS 2000'' in this Newark suburb first reached a consensus on
the roadblocks that have kept the medical community and social
service groups from reducing the virus' spread in black
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The experts devised strategies for attacking the problem,
including seeking help from churches and universities, lobbying for
more money to help community AIDS groups and getting doctors, peer
counselors and everyone else possible to encourage blacks to get
HIV screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ''To bring this cadre of people together in one room was worth
as much as any grant,'' because of all the information and ideas
shared, said Debra Fraser-Howe, president of the National Black
Leadership Commission on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Conference co-moderator Dr. Beny Primm said assembling top
experts from so many fields to focus on the crisis was ''a
milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of new AIDS cases in this country each year is
ebbing, African-Americans make up a growing percentage of newly
diagnosed patients. Blacks comprised 61 percent of the HIV
infections reported in 1999 and 54 percent of those reported in
1998, according to conference sponsor Glaxo Wellcome, a drug
company that makes AIDS medications.
</P>
<P>
   ''What made this meeting unique is that now we'll see (the
pharmaceutical) industry working with government, industry working
with social service agencies ... in major cities with rates of HIV
that are high,'' said Primm, who is executive director of the
Brooklyn, N.Y.-based Addiction Research and Treatment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The conference drew officials from federal health agencies such
as the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the
Department of Health and Human Services, members of the
Congressional Black Caucus, representatives of national and local
AIDS advocacy and service groups, physicians and representatives of
Research Triangle Park, N.C.-based Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must foster public-private partnerships and bring together
multiple agencies such as (Housing and Urban Development), the
Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Agriculture and the
Small Business Administration to redirect federal funding to the
communities that need it most,'' said Dr. Donna Christensen, who
also is the congresswoman representing the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which focused on the AIDS epidemic in black
communities in the Northeast, also drew city officials from Boston,
New York, Newark, Philadelphia, Baltimore, Washington, D.C.,
Wilmington, Del., Providence, R.I., and New Haven and Hartford, Ct.
</P>
<P>
   After a follow-up conference in a few months, when the same
officials and experts plan to discuss progress and develop
additional strategies, Primm expects future conferences in other
U.S. regions where AIDS patients may find even less support from
family, government and charities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to become a nationwide effort,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Among the goals set by the summit's participants:
</P>
<P>
   --getting African-American churches to help change attitudes
about AIDS;
</P>
<P>
   --fostering grass-roots projects that train social service
providers, peer counselors and other community members -- as well as
medical professionals -- to identify people at risk and persuade
them to be tested for HIV infection;
</P>
<P>
   --developing partnerships between community organizations and
universities;
</P>
<P>
   --helping community AIDS groups get the infrastructure support
they need to compete for and sustain government funding for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said stringent federal documentation requirements make
it hard for community groups, operating without professional grant
writers, attorneys and other key personnel, to get and keep federal
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ability to provide the best services and the ability to
prove how well the service was delivered are not the same,'' said
Rashidah Hassan, a registered nurse and assistant director of
Circle of Care, a decade-old Philadelphia AIDS services group.
</P>
<P>
   Primm also said politicians and activists who attended plan to
lobby for changes in rules for receiving federal block grants for
AIDS programs so communities with a high AIDS infection rate can
apply even if the rest of their city or state has a lower rate.
Rules now are based on an entire state's infection rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-20-00 1834 </TRAILER>
