<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Party Activities Frozen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The government on Saturday froze the
activities of an Islamic-oriented party in reaction to a recent
leadership split within the organization, judicial officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two senior members of the Labor Party -- which is blamed for
recent student riots -- split from the group Tuesday, denouncing
party leader Ibrahim Shukri and each claiming to be the new leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Political Parties Committee, a government body that licenses
political groups, said Saturday it does not recognize any of the
three men claiming to lead the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdi Ahmed, a movie actor and a member of the party's Central
Committee, and Ahmed Idriss, also on the 14-member committee, were
chosen in separate rallies to replace Shukri, who has led the party
since its establishment in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed and Idriss have accused Shukri and Labor Party
Secretary-General Adel Hussein of turning the party into an Islamic
fundamentalist group and inciting sedition.
</P>
<P>
   The committee on Saturday referred the party to a public
prosecutor, who will investigate the sedition charges, as well as
allegations of financial and administrative irregularities. The
prosecutor also will decide whether the party should be banned.
</P>
<P>
   The party should resolve the leadership problem itself, the
committee said, or take the question to court, the judicial
officials said on condition their names not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein told Qatar's Al-Jazeera Television on Saturday that the
committee's action against the party -- including the closing of its
newspaper -- was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been considering a ban on the party and its
newspaper, Al-Shaab, since a May 5 article in the party journal
prompted two days of student riots. The article said a book
approved by the Culture Ministry for publication in Egypt was
blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   On May 7 and 8, hundreds of Muslim students demonstrated against
the book, clashing with police. At least 40 students and six
policemen were injured in the riots. Police arrested 75 students.
</P>
<P>
   Culture Ministry officials said the 1983 book, ''Banquet for
Seaweed,'' by Syrian author Haider Haider, was reprinted as part of
a series of classics of Arabic literature. Literary experts
appointed by the ministry have said the novel does not defame
religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
