<HEADLINE> Americans Polled on Clinton Support  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-thirds of Americans think President
Clinton would run for office again if he could, but only a third
believe he would win, said a poll released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's biggest achievements during his term in office have
been the strong economy and deficit reduction, according to the
CBS-New York Times poll released Saturday. While Clinton's job
approval remains at six of 10 Americans, even though only a fourth
of the public feel he has honesty and integrity. The president is
constitutionally barred from seeking office for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Four of 10 said they would consider voting for him if he ran
again, the poll suggested. About the same number said in the poll
that they support Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic presidential nominee. Gore was slightly behind
Republican rival George W. Bush in head-to-head results released
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Americans thought Clinton combines the best qualities of Bush
and Gore. Clinton has the same ratings on leadership as Bush and
the same ratings as Gore for caring about people. But his ratings
on honesty and integrity were significantly below both; one-fourth
said Clinton could be trusted, while four in 10 said that of Bush
and of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll was conducted May 10-13 among 947 adults and
has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1914 </TRAILER>
