<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Economy Grows .3 Percent  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A key economic indicator
showed
Venezuela moving out of its worst recession in a decade.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Venezuela's gross domestic product grew .3 percent in the first
quarter versus the same period last year, according to Central Bank
figures. Gross domestic product is the total value of goods and
services produced locally in a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The private sector grew by 1.8 percent in the first quarter of
this year, offsetting a 1.9 percent contraction in the public
sector.
</P>
<P>
   The oil-dependent economy had been mired in a deep recession
since the third quarter of 1998 when GDP shrank by 5.3 percent,
initiating eight quarters of consecutive contractions. In 1999, GDP
plunged 7.2 percent, the worst drop since 1989, despite soaring oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The recession resulted in the loss of 600,000 jobs last year and
the closing of 1,000 industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics blamed last year's economic contraction on President
Hugo Chavez' aggressive antibusiness rhetoric and political
uncertainty due to a change of constitutions, two factors they say
alienated private investors.
</P>
<P>
   News of economic growth comes just one week before a
presidential election, in which Chavez is seeking re-election. The
charismatic president remains widely popular among the country's
poor masses and is expected to win the vote handily, despite last
year's recession.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter growth contradicted economists' predictions of
a 2 percent drop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 1915 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0119 </DOCNO>
