<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets 8, Diamondbacks 7  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Hampton made the wait worthwhile for the
few Mets fans who stuck around Shea Stadium through a 3-hour,
31-minute rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   Unaffected by the later start, Hampton pitched six scoreless
innings and hit a two-run single as the New York Mets held off the
Arizona Diamondbacks 8-7 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona rallied for five runs in the ninth, capped by Kelly
Stinnett's two-out, two-run single off John Franco. Armando Benitez
relieved with runners at first and second and struck out
pinch-hitter Erubiel Durazo for his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won three straight games for the first time since
their nine-game winning streak ended April 25. Along with seeing a
win, the home fans who weathered the delay were given a free ticket
to a later game.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks committed four errors and have lost five of six
games following a nine-game winning streak. They have lost four
straight games in Shea Stadium, including two in last year's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous start to his New York career, Hampton (5-4)
has finally started pitching like the ace the Mets thought they
acquired from Houston last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander has allowed only one run in 23 1-3 innings in
his last three starts, lowering his ERA from 6.52 to 4.21. He
allowed four hits and one walk Saturday before leaving with
tightness in his upper back.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was also in the middle of two Mets' scoring rallies.
After Rey Ordonez led off the third inning with a single off Omar
Daal (1-5), Hampton laid down a bunt. Daal barehanded the ball,
wheeled and threw high to second base for an error.
</P>
<P>
   After a sacrifice bunt by Joe McEwing, Derek Bell hit an infield
single to score the first run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets broke the game open with five runs in the fourth. Benny
Agbayani, Jay Payton and Ordonez hit one-out singles to load the
bases. Payton's hit snapped an 0-for-23 slump.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton then reached out and lined a single to center to make it
3-0. The Mets added three more runs on an error by second baseman
Jay Bell, another RBI single by Bell and a sacrifice fly by Edgardo
Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo added a two-run homer in the seventh inning off Greg
Swindell.
</P>
<P>
   After the lengthy rain delay before the start of the game, fewer
than 10,000 fans were left from the paid crowd of 37,121. Hampton
came out firing strikes -- something he had trouble doing early this
season -- throwing 13 straight to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton had spotless control all day, throwing 57 of 79 pitches
for strikes. After the Mets went ahead 6-0 in the fourth inning, he
needed only 18 pitches to work through his final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Colbrunn hit a two-run homer in the eighth off Pat Mahomes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rain delay, fans from the game could get free
tickets to an additional game on June 20 or 21 against
Philadelphia, or June 26 or 27 against Florida.
Notes: Hampton, who walked 36 batters in his first 38 2-3 innings,
has allowed only two walks in his last 23 1-3 innings. ... Daal
allowed six runs -- four earned -- and eight hits in 3 1-3 innings.
... The Diamondbacks are 3-5 on their nine-game road trip, losing
one of three in San Diego, two of three in Montreal and the first
two in New York. Their last losing road trip came from June 29-July
5 last season when they went 2-5 on a trip to Cincinnati and St.
Louis. ... Arizona's Tony Womack singled in the sixth inning to tie
his career high with a 16-game hitting streak. ... Arizona OF Steve
Finley was scratched after being hit on the right elbow by a pitch
Friday. Travis Lee got his first career start in center field and
made a two-base error in the seventh inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
