<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mo. Abortion Law Creates Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT CHARTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Four terminally ill newborns were kept on
life support at a state-run hospital against their parents' wishes
out of fears that doctors could be charged with murder under
Missouri's new law banning a type of late-term abortion, the
babies' attending physician said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in legal straitjackets with our hands tied behind our
backs,'' said Dr. John Pardalos, a specialist in neonatal intensive
care at University Hospital and Clinics in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   All four infants, born since the passage of the 1999 law,
eventually died while on ventilators to assist their breathing,
Pardalos said. Some died in just a few days, but one lived 2{ weeks
after the parents asked to withdraw life-sustaining treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Pardalos said the events turned parents' grief into ''hatred of
the political system.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law, meant to ban what opponents call ''partial-birth''
abortion, makes doctors guilty of ''infanticide'' if they purposely
cause a living infant's death ''by an overt act performed when the
infant is partially born or born.'' The crime is equivalent to
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the law's definition of a ''living infant'' is a child
''who has not attained the age of 30 days post-birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The abortion foe who wrote the law said the hospital lawyers
were wrong to advise the doctors for the four terminally ill
newborns that the law may apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that's their legal advice, they're not lawyers,'' said
Louis DeFeo, chief lawyer lobbyist for the Missouri Catholic
Conference. He said the law specifically excuses doctors practicing
''usual and customary standards of medical practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a difference between acting with the intent to cause
death and knowing that to withdraw a treatment, death could be a
consequence,'' DeFeo said. ''If you are simply making a medical
judgment, that's not a crime. It's not a crime for a baby or for a
90-year old.''
</P>
<P>
   As in other states where ''partial-birth'' bans have been
overturned, Missouri's law is being challenged in federal court on
the grounds that it also limits otherwise legal kinds of abortions.
The law is on hold for now while the lawsuit is pending.
</P>
<P>
   But the ''waiting period'' in the law of 30 days after birth has
so far not been challenged. So Marvin E. ''Bunkie'' Wright, the
University of Missouri's general counsel, said he is telling school
doctors not to withdraw life support from infants younger than 30
days, despite parents' demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the way it is until they receive a court order or court
opinion,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   A check of other Missouri hospitals with large numbers of births
found no restriction similar to those at the university hospital,
which delivered 1,244 babies last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert M. Nelson, chairman of the Bioethics Committee of the
55,000-member American Academy of Pediatrics, reviewed the Missouri
law and said he had heard of no similar restrictions anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't imagine the Legislature intended this bill to bar
withdrawing support from an infant who is going to die,'' said
Nelson, a neonatologist at Children's Hospital of Wisconsin. ''If
it was intended, it's going against decisions parents and
physicians make every day around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was passed last year after Missouri's Legislature
overrode the veto of Gov. Mel Carnahan, who supports abortion
rights and has argued that it puts doctors at risk of prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 2028 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000520.0133 </DOCNO>
