could be charged with murder under Missouri's new law banning a type of
late-term abortion, the babies' attending physician said. ''We are in legal
straitjackets with our hands tied behind our backs,'' said Dr. John Pardalos, a
specialist in neonatal intensive care at University Hospital and Clinics in
Columbia. All four infants, born since the passage of the 1999 law, eventually
died while on ventilators to assist their breathing, Pardalos said.
