<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freedman Wins Olympic Cycling Trial  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Nicole Freedman has a Stanford education
that isn't directly linked to her current job. She has an appetite
for ''greaseburgers.'' She lives in an old van, parked next to a
friend's home.
</P>
<P>
   And Freedman has a ticket to the Sydney Olympics, by virtue of
her victory Saturday in the U.S. Olympic cycling trials road race.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman won by about 1{ bike-lengths over Pam Schuster of
Northridge, Calif., and third-place Mina Pizzini of Philadelphia.
Each was timed in 2 hours, 38 minutes, 56 seconds on the relatively
flat 64-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   The men's winner was Antonio Cruz, 28, of Long Beach, Calif.,
who won in 5:21.31, also by sprinting for the finish line after 138
miles. His wheel crossed just ahead of Derek Bouchard-Hall of Palo
Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Saturn trade team, Cruz was assigned to help
place teammate Frank McCormack in a position to win. When McCormack
broke away with a kilometer to go, other riders stayed with him.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz kept pace at the rear of the lead pack. When the riders
jockeyed within sight of the finish line, Cruz -- last year's
national criterium champion -- got the best route and raced harder
in the final 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew someone was going to jump early, someone who wasn't
known to be a sprinter,'' Cruz said. ''That's all I wanted to key
off with 400 or 500 meters to the line. ... It made it the perfect
race for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz raised his arms and let out a whoop as he sped across the
finish line, with Bouchard-Hall and third-place racer Frankie
Andreu of Dearborn, Mich., narrowly behind him.
</P>
<P>
   After he stopped, Cruz folded his hands and said a prayer of
thanks as his eyes welled with tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just so happy,'' he said. ''I tend to get pretty
emotional, especially with a big win. All the support that I've
had, it's running through my mind right now. It keeps me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman, who turns 28 on Sunday, focused her training
exclusively on the road race, the only event where U.S. Cycling
officials promised an Olympic trip for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was my only goal of the year,'' Freedman said. ''I kept
telling myself I could win this.''
</P>
<P>
   Other positions on the American track, road and mountain bike
cycling teams will be determined this summer by coaches and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman went to high school in Wellesley, Mass., spent two
years at MIT and transferred to Stanford. She was on the Cardinal
track team but got into cycling after struggling as a junior to
remain competitive as a runner.
</P>
<P>
   Riding was a comfortable fit, and Freedman earned a degree in
urban planning, although she now works for a women's sports
marketing firm. She lives in a van that remains parked at a
friend's home.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's had the same tank of gas since 1996,'' she said. ''If I
jump-start it, I can get it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing her chances of making the Olympic squad as a coaches'
pick were unlikely, Freedman focused on road race. Her favorite
training spot is a stretch of road near the Stanford campus called
Coyote Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great way to build power for the sprints and work on
speed going down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman was part of a six-member group that broke from the main
pack with about 25 miles remaining. Her strength is sprinting, and
she pulled away over the final kilometer then powered up a 200-yard
incline to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hats off to Nicole,'' Schuster said. ''She totally earned
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When she crossed the line, Freedman raised her right arm and
pumped her fist. A short distance up the road, she collapsed on the
pavement in a fit of joy, then hugged anybody within 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a dream come true,'' she said. ''I didn't believe it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate, Freedman plans to visit a Stanford-area hangout,
Eat at Eric's, that tempted her but was off limits during training.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to have a double greaseburger, fries and a root
beer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz grew up in Whittier, Calif., and became interested in
cycling after his father, Carlos, took him to see the road race
during the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A standout on the junior circuit, the younger Cruz ''lost that
spark for racing'' during the early 1990s. He found it again five
years later while living in Reno, Nev., and attending an area road
race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I watched guys who I had raced against,'' Cruz recalled. ''I
was just a spectator but I felt like I was in the race. I was
watching moves unfold, knowing I could be there. I knew I still had
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He resumed training the next week and now he'll ride in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   After Cruz won on Saturday, a jaded competitor told him, ''Have
fun riding for Lance,'' suggesting Cruz will be asked to help
reigning Tour de France champ Lance Armstrong of Austin, Texas,
secure the Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure I'll have a role, but my role here today wasn't to
win,'' Cruz said. ''Anything could happen. You never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
