<HEADLINE> McCain Urges Vt. GOP on Bush  </HEADLINE>
By LISA RATHKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain thanked Vermont
Republicans on Saturday for their support in the presidential
primary earlier this year and urged them to come together now for
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask all the McCain supporters -- Republican, independent,
independent-minded Democrats -- to join us in electing Governor Bush
as president of the United States. ... Now is the time for unity,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A bid by McCain supporters to control the Vermont delegation at
the party's national convention this summer was dashed when
Republicans nominated a majority of Bush-supporting delegates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain later crossed into New Hampshire to support the
re-election of Rep. Charles Bass, one of Bush's earliest
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a natural logical question to say, 'Why are you
campaigning for Charlie Bass when he endorsed Governor Bush?'
McCain told reporters. ''I think the answer is obvious: If I only
campaigned for people who endorsed me in my campaign, my activities
would be severely restricted.''
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated that he and Bush agree more ''a lot more things
than we disagree on'' and said he expected to be back in New
Hampshire in four years -- campaigning for Bush's re-election as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion over Vermont's method of electing delegates lingered
at the state's convention.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCain won Vermont's presidential primary in March with
60 percent of the vote, he was supposedly was entitled to all of
the Vermont's 12 delegates and 12 alternatives. But the convention
rules did not require that individuals loyal to McCain in the
primary actually be selected delegates and an attempt to change the
system Saturday was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the state convention were allowed to vote for any
of the nominees for delegates to the national convention. Bush
backers won nine of the 12 slots, while McCain supporters won
three.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the party in the next four years has to make a change
in the way we go about electing delegates,'' said state Sen. Peter
Brownell of Chittenden, head of the McCain campaign in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Patrick Garahan, who is a Bush
supporter, agreed. ''I think the whole election law needs to be
looked at, particularly in this case. If I were a McCain supporter,
I'd be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the makeup of the Vermont delegation, McCain asked
Vermont GOP members to draw on shared Republican principles to back
Bush, the governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the strength of our party,'' said the Arizona senator.
''Healthy debate, shared principles, shared ideals, shared goals.
The party of Abraham Lincoln, Theodore Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan,
and adherence to those principles.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was confident Bush would restore ''integrity and
purpose to the highest office'' and he pledged to do all that he
could to ensure Vice President Al Gore, the putative Democratic
nominee, is defeated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-20-00 2223 </TRAILER>
