<HEADLINE> Saturday's Baseball Game Notes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: When Shane Spencer's hamstring tightened up in
Saturday's 3-2 loss to the Indians, Lance Johnson found himself
playing left field for the first time since Sept. 10, 1990. In the
seventh inning, Johnson was unable to come up with a diving catch
on Enrique Wilson's as Cleveland rallied to tie it. ''It had been
awhile,'' said Johnson, who recently had been working out in left.
... Jeff Nelson had his seven-game winning streak stopped when he
walked four in the ninth, including Roberto Alomar to push home the
winning run. And for all his success, Nelson has 17 walks in 24 2-3
innings this season. ... If losing Saturday meant breaking Chuck
Finley's hex over the Yankees, then that was fine with manager Joe
Torre. ''We had some good at-bats against him,'' Torre said of
Finley, 16-9 in his career vs. New York. ''That's a far cry from
early on when he would dispense of us 1-2-3.''
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Chuck Finley doesn't particularly care for his
''Yankee Killer'' nickname, and he knows there are plenty of other
dangerous teams in the AL. ''I'm not all hyped up over the
Yankees,'' he said. ''Last year, it was the Boston Red Sox that
beat Cleveland. I think we have to beat 'em all.'' ... OF David
Justice missed his second straight game with a tender hamstring.
... The comeback over New York put some excitement back in the
Indians clubhouse which got rowdier when players and coaches
gathered to watch the Preakness Stakes. ... Saturday's win via a
walk-off walk, was the second time in Jacobs Field history the
Indians had won at home on a bases-loaded walk. On June 1, 1994,
the Indians beat the Angels 3-2 in 10 innings when Mike Butcher
walked pinch-hitter Rene Gonzalez.
White Sox-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: James Baldwin is 14-1 with a 2.50 ERA while pitching
indoors. ... Baldwin is 4-0 at SkyDome. ... Nine of Baldwin's 15
earned runs have come via the home run. ... The White Sox have won
six straight at SkyDome. ... Frank Thomas went 3-for-3 with two
walks.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: RHP Roy Halladay, who started the season in Toronto's
rotation, gave up six runs on seven hits in five innings for
Triple-A Syracuse on Saturday. The Buffalo Bisons scored three runs
in the first, and three more in the fifth. ... David Wells had his
consecutive win streak stopped at six. ... Nine of Carlos Delgado's
12 home runs have been solo shots.
Tigers-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Manager Phil Garner knows his team's weakness is
hitting with runners in scoring position. The Tigers entered
Saturday's game against Boston hitting just .199 with runners in
scoring position. ''We need to get (hits) when guys are on base,''
he said. ''We're the worst team in the league with guys in scoring
position. There's nothing more I can say about it. I've been over
it a thousand times. Maybe not a thousand. I've been over it about
25 times.'' They were 2-for-5 Saturday, including Bobby Higginson's
RBI double in the fourth inning. ... Juan Gonzalez is 9-for-20 in
his last five games with six RBIs. ... Dave Mlicki has won his last
two against New York and Boston, giving up just two runs and seven
hits in 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Tim Wakefield suffered a bruised left calf when he was
hit by Jose Macias' seventh-inning liner, and is listed as
day-to-day. ... The Red Sox's staff, which shut out Toronto on
Wednesday and the Tigers on Friday, was looking for three straight
shutouts for the first time since collecting three in a series at
Toronto in August of 1990. ... Pete Schourek, Saturday's starter,
has given up one earned run in his last two starts, covering 13
innings.
Orioles-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: On Saturday morning, Red Oak High School in the
Dallas suburbs dedicated its baseball field as Buddy Groom Field.
The Orioles reliever is a 1983 graduate of the high school, where
he was an all-district outfielder as a senior. ... Orioles starter
Mike Mussina began Saturday night with the third-highest winning
percentage in road games in major league history among starters
with at least 100 road decisions who began their career 1900 or
later. Mussina's .660 winning percentage (68-35) ranks behind
Whitey Ford's .695 (116-51) and Christy Mathewson's .665 (183-92).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Rangers LHP Kenny Rogers' availability for next week is
still in doubt. Rogers has been bothered by a sore left shoulder
and Sunday night will mark the second start he's missed. Rogers is
scheduled to throw on the side Sunday. If he comes through that
session without pain, Rogers could be ready to pitch Wednesday
night in Oakland. Manager Johnny Oates said a start on Saturday
against Seattle might be more realistic. ... Rogers has a swollen
eye from an accidental punch while playing with his 3-year-old son.
... Friday night's home rainout was the first for the Rangers since
Sept. 5, 1999.
Twins-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Brad Radke pitched the 19th complete game of his
career on Friday night, and first this season. It was also
Minnesota's second complete game. ''You want to try and pitch nine
innings every time you go out,'' Radke said. ''It doesn't matter
who you face, you don't want to give up any runs.'' Radke's last
complete game was on Sept. 5 last year at Tampa Bay. ... Denny
Hocking started Saturday's game at 3B, his 10th appearance at the
position this season. He's played everywhere but catcher and
pitcher this year, also playing nine games each at second base and
right field. It doesn't seem to matter where he plays against the
Oakland A's. He tied his career high with five hits against them on
Thursday and is 9-for-13 with three walks, a home run and four RBIs
in the first three games of the four-game series which concludes
Sunday. He's reached base safely in 15 of his last 20 plate
appearances against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: DH John Jaha is ready to start a rehab assignment, but
the question is where? The A's are leaning toward sending him to
their extended spring training facility in Arizona when the team
leaves for a nine-game road trip on Monday. Jaha would prefer to
face live pitching in a real game. ''I would love to go with
(Triple-A affiliate) Sacramento,'' Jaha said. ''But I'll go where
they want me to go. It's hard to tell right now how far along I am
because I'm swinging off a tee.'' Jaha has been on the disabled
list since April 24 with a strained left shoulder and sore elbow.
''We don't want to take any unnecessary chances,'' A's manager Art
Howe said. ''We want John healthy.''... 3B Eric Chavez didn't start
Saturday because the Twins had a left-hander on the mound. Chavez
is batting .147 against left-handers. He's also 2-for-24 (.083) on
the current homestand.
Devil Rays-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL RAYS: Esteban Yan had a career-high eight strikeouts in
his 12th career start for Tampa Bay. His previous high was seven.
... The Devil Rays are 9-9 in one-run games this season. ... Miguel
Cairo was 3-for-4 Saturday, making him .365 (27-for-74) in his
career against the Mariners. ... Roberto Hernandez recorded his
237th career save, most by a pitcher born outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: In addition to his 76th career leadoff home run, Rickey
Henderson walked twice, giving him 1,999 for his career. He's third
on the career list and needs 20 to tie Ted Williams (2,019) for
second place. ... Four Mariners pitchers walked eight batters. ...
Edgar Martinez is hitting .448 (30-for-67) in May with seven home
runs and 17 RBIs.
Royals-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: RHP Jerry Spradlin has more saves on the Royals'
current road trip (three) than he's had in any season; his previous
career high was two, in 1993 with Cincinnati. ... Kansas City's
bullpen had blown nine of 14 save opportunities before Spradlin
found his groove. ... The Royals' May 9 rainout in Detroit was
officially re-scheduled as part of a July 22 day-night
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Pitcher Kent Mercker, hospitalized since suffering
cerebral bleeding May 11, is expected to be discharged from UCI
Medical Center on Monday. ... Injuries have left the Angels thin in
pitching, but Ramon Ortiz, who started the season in their
rotation, is not a candidate to be brought back from Edmonton. In
two starts there, Ortiz has given up six runs, lasting a total of
only 2 1-3 innings. ... Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, disabled since
May 8 with a tight shoulder, continues to consider surgery, which
would end his season.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Reds-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Reds starter Ron Villone threw 127 pitches Saturday
in winning his fourth straight start. ''I had no idea,'' he said.
''My arm felt great and I felt like I could have thrown another
100.'' Villone had all three of his walks in the first two innings
before settling down. ''The ball was all over the place. I battled
myself,'' he added. ... Reliever Danny Graves is the first Reds
pitcher to start a season 6-0 since Johnny Ruffin in 1994. No Cincy
pitcher has gone 7-0 since Ron Robinson or 8-0 since Mike LaCoss in
1979. Graves is also 7-for-7 in save opportunities. ... The Reds
are 10-1 when Ken Griffey Jr. homers and eight of his 13 homers
have tied or put them ahead. ... Reds bullpen coach Tom Hume is
donating $50 to the Shriners Hospital in Cincinnati for every win
and save by a Reds reliever. So far, he's donated $1,150 for nine
wins and 14 saves.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: LHP Scott Downs, who's made eight starts, is headed to
the bullpen until next Saturday when he'll get another start
against San Francisco. ... Manager Don Baylor said he will try to
play OF Henry Rodriguez in Sunday's series finale against the Reds.
Rodriguez has been sidelined with a bruised knee after fouling a
ball off it Tuesday. Yankees scout Gene Michael was at the game
again Saturday and is believed to be scouting Rodriguez for a
possible trade. ''He's on special assignment. Mr. Steinbrenner sent
him here to look at a player. I don't know if it will result in
anything,'' Baylor said of Michael. ''George believes in him
(Michael). If they want to make a deal, they will.'' However,
Rodriguez is not interested in leaving: ''I don't want to be
traded. I want to stay here,'' he said. According to published
reports, the potential deal would send Ricky Ledee and a reliever
to the Cubs for Rodriguez. ... Baylor said the Cubs might place 3B
Shane Andrews on the disabled list because of a bad back.
Astros-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The Astros entered the game with a 199-157 mark against
the Expos, including a 96-83 record in Montreal. ... Astros manager
Larry Dierker is two wins away from his 300th career win. Dierker
has a 298-227 mark since becoming Houston's manager following the
1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos were looking to claim their eighth series in
their last 10 Saturday night, following a 3-2 win Friday in 10
innings. It was Montreal's first extra-inning game of the season
and first win in extra innings at Olympic Stadium since Aug. 4,
1998. The Expos were 0-7 in extra innings at home last season. ...
LHP Jim Poole and RHP Guillermo Mota both joined the team Saturday.
Poole, 33, was signed by Montreal as a free agent Friday after
being released by Detroit two days earlier. Mota was recalled from
Triple-A Ottawa when RHP Anthony Telford was placed on the 15-day
disabled list Friday due to tendinitis in his right shoulder. INF
Trace Coquillette was optioned to Ottawa, and C Bob Henley was
moved from the 15-day to 60-day disabled list to make room for
Poole on the 40-man roster.
Rockies-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Phillies 3B Scott Rolen sat out the game and will
not play Sunday because of soreness in his legs and back. ''I'm not
complaining, but the fact is the turf has caught up with me,''
Rolen said. Rolen, who leads the Phillies in home runs (12) and
RBIs (27) has played on turf in 19 of his last 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: So far this season, Colorado has had four weather
postponements, two rain-delayed games, a Coors Field power outage,
and Friday night, the game was delayed for 12 minutes because the
umpires arrived late. ... On Friday night, Pedro Astacio threw 119
pitches, 66 for strikes. In the club's previous game on Wednesday
against New York, Rolando Arrojo threw the exact same amount of
pitches and strike.
Dodgers-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers are 6-1 on Fridays. ... Eric Karros'
11-game hitting streak was snapped Friday. He hit .381 with five
homers and 13 RBIs during the streak. ... Dodgers broadcaster Vin
Scully was in New York on Friday to deliver the commencement speech
at Fordham University where he was bestowed an honorary degree of
Doctor of Humane Letters. Scully will rejoin the Dodgers in time
for Sunday's game. Ross Porter and Rick Monday called the game
Friday. ... SS Alex Cora, who started Friday, was playing in South
Florida for the first time since the Dodgers drafted him out of the
University of Miami in the third round of the 1996 draft. ... The
Dodgers failed to hit a home run Friday for the 10th time in 39
games this season. They've hit 64, and are on pace to hit 266 home
runs. The major league record is 266, set by the 1997 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: IF Kevin Millar was scratched from the starting lineup
after taking a line drive off his left foot Friday night. Millar,
filling in for injured 3B Mike Lowell, was replaced by utilityman
Dave Berg. ... 2B Luis Castillo's eight-game hitting streak was
snapped Friday, as was his streak of 14 consecutive steals, two shy
of tying his own team record of 16 straight.
Cardinals-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: After batting cleanup in his first 30 starts, Mark
McGwire batted third for the second night in a row Saturday.
Manager Tony La Russa wanted some left-handed batters around
McGwire to keep the Pirates' right-handed starters -- Kris Benson on
Friday and Francisco Cordova on Saturday -- from pitching around
him. ... Former Pirates manager Jim Leyland, now a Cardinals scout,
shagged throws for La Russa during batting practice. Leyland, lives
in Pittsburgh, was La Russa's third-base coach with the White Sox
before becoming the Pirates manager in 1986. ... 2B Fernando Vina,
who left Friday night's 13-1 loss to Pittsburgh after being struck
in the calf by a Kris Benson pitch, returned to the lineup
Saturday. ... The Cardinals have been outscored 23-8 in rookie
left-hander Rick Ankiel's two starts against the Pirates. Ankiel
allowed seven runs and seven hits in 2 2-3 innings Friday,
prompting pitching coach Dave Duncan to say, ''You can't say you're
surprised, because at this stage of his career he's still
developing. There are still some things he doesn't do consistently
yet. You hope he'll do that as time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Wil Cordero returned to the Pirates lineup after
missing four games to return to Puerto Rico for a child custody
hearing. Cordero was granted temporary custody of his two children,
ages 2 and 3, by the wife he is now divorcing. ... The Pirates have
used six leadoff batters, including 2B Warren Morris, who led off
Saturday for the second time this season. C Jason Kendall began the
season as the leadoff hitter, was dropped to third during a
team-wide batting slump and now is batting second. ... After this
weekend, the Pirates don't face an NL Central team again until they
play the Cubs on June 27. ... Todd Ritchie, a 15-game winner last
season who starts Sunday against the Cardinals, has lasted only
eight innings in his last two starts. ... RHP Rich Loiselle, who
had 29 saves as a rookie in 1997, continues on a rehabilitation
program at Double-A Altoona but is not close to returning to the
majors. He had reconstructive right elbow surgery in July, and has
not regained the velocity he had three seasons ago.
Diamondbacks-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Tony Womack singled in the sixth inning to tie his
career high with a 16-game hitting streak. In an official scoring
change, Womack was credited with a single in the seventh inning of
Friday night's game instead of reaching base on an error by 1B Todd
Zeile. ... Closer Matt Mantei will likely be activated from the DL
Sunday. The Diamondbacks haven't missed him much as the bullpen has
a 1.55 ERA the last 15 games entering Saturday's action. Overall,
Arizona's relievers are second in the league with 2.95 ERA. ... OF
Steve Finley was scratched after being hit on the right elbow by a
pitch Friday night. Travis Lee got his first career start in center
field. ... 3B Matt Williams went 1-for-4 Friday night for Double-A
El Paso as he rehabs his broken right foot. Williams is 5-for-11 at
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The game was delayed 3 hours, 31 minutes by rain.
Because of the delay, fans from the game could get free tickets to
an additional game on June 20 or 21 against Philadelphia, or June
26 or 27 against Florida. ... Mike Hampton threw 13 straight
strikes to open the game. ... 3B Robin Ventura was sidelined with a
sore left thigh and could be out a few days. Joe McEwing started in
his place. ... Melvin Mora, on the DL with a cut right index
finger, will have stitches taken out Sunday. ... Jay Payton snapped
an 0-for-23 slump with a single in the fourth.
Padres-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: OF Tony Gwynn, plagued by injuries all season, was
out of the lineup again after hurting his left knee running the
bases Friday night. Gwynn twisted his knee in the third inning
while trying to get back to first after a single. He remained in
the game for a couple of more innings, leaving for a pinch-runner
after going 3-for-3 to raise his average from .196 to .241. But the
knee was still bothering Gwynn 24 hours later, so Eric Owens
started in right. ''It's sore right now,'' manager Bruce Bochy
said, adding that he hopes Gwynn can return to the lineup Monday
when the Padres return home for a series against the New York Mets.
Gwynn played in only 16 of San Diego's first 41 games.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: 2B Quilvio Veras was hobbling in the clubhouse, his
right knee heavily taped after being struck by a pitch in the first
inning Friday night. A severe bruise caused him to be replaced in
the lineup by Keith Lockhart. ''It's going to take a couple of days
to get back,'' Veras said. ... P Tom Glavine, who was sick Friday
night and didn't come to the ballpark, took part in batting
practice before heading home. He is expected to take his regular
turn in the rotation Sunday. ... Ned Yost IV, the son of third-base
coach Ned Yost, played this weekend in the finals of Georgia's
Class AAAA playoffs with Lassiter High School. Lassiter was
defeated in the deciding game Saturday by Lowndes High, 13-5.
Giants-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: The Giants' 11-10 loss in 10 innings Friday night
was their seventh straight, their longest streak of the season and
two more than their longest last season. The seven losses were all
on the road. ... The Giants entered Saturday night's game against
Milwaukee second-to-last in the NL with 36 errors for a .976
fielding average on 1,472 total chances. ... Mark Gardner made his
300th career appearance and 243rd start Saturday night in the game
against Milwaukee. He returned to the starting rotation to replace
Joe Nathan, who is on the disabled list with tendinitis in his
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers had won their last two games heading into
Saturday night's contest against the Giants, but it wasn't easy.
The games encompassed 26 innings, one 16-innings, with an elapsed
time of 10 hours. ... The Brewers said they will call up pitcher
Jamey Wright from a rehabilitation assignment in Triple-A to start
next Tuesday against the Braves. He has been on the disabled list
since March 28 with a sub-surface rotator cuff tear in his right
shoulder. ... Outfielder Geoff Jenkins, out since May 6 with a
broken right middle finger, has had the splint taken off his
injured finger. But it may take a week to 10 days before he can
return to the lineup.
</P>
