<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Counterterrorism Test Begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The largest-ever field test of the nation's
ability to respond to a terrorist attack with chemical or
biological weapons began Saturday, involving Cabinet secretaries,
governors and municipal leaders in two cities.
</P>
<P>
   The counterterrorism exercise called ''TOPOFF'' involved a
simulated chemical attack on Portsmouth, N.H., followed by a
simulated biological weapon attack in Denver. The $3.5 million
program, mandated by Congress was paid for by the Department of
Justice and the federal Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The Portsmouth scenario involved an explosion at a mock charity
event that led to a number of ''fatalities'' and ''injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a test of people's abilities to respond to what has
happened,'' said Mike Beeman, FEMA spokesman in Portsmouth.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire exercise involved a simulated explosion at the
New Hampshire Port Authority that left dozens of people at a mock
charity run with imaginary injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Though local officials knew their communities had been selected
for the terrorism test, they did not know it would begin Saturday.
They were told only that it would take place sometime in May.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Van Dongen, spokesman for the state Office of Emergency
Management, said that around 8 a.m. Saturday, emergency crews were
called to respond to a van explosion at the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the police and fire equipment arrived they figured out
pretty quickly they had more than just explosion victims because
that explosion expelled some sort of chemical agent,'' Van Dongen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem for the first responders was to figure out what
they had, how to contain it, how to treat the victims and how to
protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Portsmouth officials quickly called for assistance from
communities as far as 50 miles away and that Gov. Jeanne Shaheen
declared a state of emergency and asked President Clinton to issue
a disaster declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Such a declaration, in the event of a actual emergency, would
qualify the state for federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Aurora, Colo., authorities responded to a simulated
biological attack on a mock hotel just outside Denver,
</P>
<P>
   ''This is their opportunity to do something that they hope
they'll never have to do in real life,'' said Division Chief Doug
Abraham of the Aurora Police Department, one of about 200 people
who participated in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   In the drill, a vacant building on the former Fitzsimons Army
Medical Center campus was turned into the make-believe Hide-Away
Hotel, where a mock maid discovered a 25-year-old man dead in his
room just after 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Under the simulation, police become suspicious because the
corpse -- played by a mannequin -- had skin lesions, blood around the
mouth and gangrene in one big toe, said FBI special agent Mark
Mershon.
</P>
<P>
   While members of actual media organizations were kept behind
police tape at the far end of the street, fake television reporters
wearing black satin ''Virtual News Network'' jackets were allowed
much closer.
</P>
<P>
   The national test was expected to last 10 days. Attorney General
Janet Reno, Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, and
FEMA Director James Lee Witt, and state and local leaders were
expected to take part.
</P>
<P>
   A separate, but related counterterrorism test was also scheduled
to start Saturday in Washington and adjacent Prince Georges County,
Md., by the FBI, FEMA, and the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   They will respond to a fake attack with an as-yet undisclosed
type of weapon of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
